<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Act in Next Few Days: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Thursday that NATO is to deliver its
planned air strikes in Kosovo in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
After meeting NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, Madeleine
Albright told a press conference that the western military
alliance was expected to act in the next few days should Belgrade
fail to comply fully with the United Nations Security Council
Resolution (UNSCR).
</P>
<P>
But Albright, scheduled to fly later in the day to London for a
meeting of the Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, said that NATO
was not giving out any deadline but time was running out.
</P>
<P>
"He (Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic) had months to
comply and now he has but a few days which is frankly what we
needed (for taking action)," said Albright.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state, who has just wound up a Middle
East trip, said that it was obvious that Belgrade failed to comply
with the UNSCR after consulting with U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
She said she was sending Holbrooke back to Belgrade after the
Contact Group meeting in London to convey a "clear and simple"
message that Milosevic must comply with a manner that is adorable
and verifiable the long-standing political, humanitarian and
military demands from the international community or face grave
consequences.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that judging by the three lengthy discussions
between Holbrooke and Milosevic, the Yugoslav president did not
understand the seriousness of the current situation.
</P>
<P>
The time was coming for NATO to authorize the activation of the
use of force, said Albright after her discussion with Solana on
the role of the allies in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
She said that she agreed with Solana's assessment that NATO had
the legitimacy to act to stop the catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
"Speaking for the United States, I believe it's time for the
alliance to move to the next phase of its decision-making and that
is to take the difficult but necessary decision to authorize
military force if Milosevic fails to comply," stressed Albright.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state said that NATO action was necessary
though Milosevic had avoided in the past few days to provoke in
the hope of driving a wedge into the unity of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
"That will not happen," said Albright. "We must be prepared to
take action because we know if we are not there, there is nothing
to stop them for going back to business as usual."
</P>
<P>
The situation on the ground in Kosovo had not changed
fundamentally, added Albright who pointed out that Yugoslav
infantry, artillery and armored units were still deployed in key
points in Kosovo and special police were still deployed heavily
along the roads and many of them were digging in for the coming
winter.
</P>
<P>
She described the Yugoslav withdrawal as a "televised show of
soldiers leaving Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
"What we need is a complete and verifiable withdrawal of the
forces responsible for the violence," said Albright.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state said that people had to take into
consideration of Milosevic's long-standing unwillingness to
negotiate seriously and the accumulated barbarities of the last
three months.
</P>
<P>
"Time and again Milosevic has promised us to do things that he
had no intention of doing and time and again he has taken
half-measures to avoid the consequences of actions," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that Milosevic was expected to continue to do the
minimum and necessary to avoid NATO action and that Milosevic had
better understand that the minimum was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
"The only thing that is good enough is full compliance," said
Albright who added that Milosevic must immediately end all
military and police operations in Kosovo and withdraw all units to
their bases in a way that can be verified, provide the
international community with unfettered access to monitoring the
situation in Kosovo, and agree to a timetable for a political
settlement based on the draft the Contact Group has endorsed and
cooperate with the war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state said that diplomats of the
six-nation Contact Group all had gone through the "extra mile" for
peace.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Western countries were telling both the
Serbians and the Kosovo ethnic Albanians that they did not support
for independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We are for Serbia out of Kosovo and not for Kosovo out of
Serbia," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
But a good diplomacy has had to know when diplomacy has reached
its limits, she added. "And we are rapidly reaching that point
now."
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the Kosovo crisis had taken to a crossroad
both the Balkans and NATO.
</P>
<P>
She described NATO as the institution of choice when it comes
to preserving peace and defending western values in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"NATO must be prepared to act when a threat of this nature
exists on Europe's doorsteps," said Albright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
