<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Arab Bank for Economic Development in Africa has
agreed to assist Mauritius in building a dam at an approximate
cost of 133 million U.S. dollars to meet the needs of potable and
irrigation waters, Thursday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" reported.
</P>
<P>
The bank has sent a delegation of experts to the island-country
to assess the feasibility of the project, but the volume of the
loan has not been divulged.
</P>
<P>
The experts' report pointed out that the Midland dam in northern
Mauritius will satisfy the needs of the region of irrigation
waters until the year 2010, and of drinking water up to the end
of 2025.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- A study made by the Tunisian Ministry of Trade
reveals that production of the textile and clothing sector has
grown five-fold over the past 10 years, occupying the first rank
among local industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia also occupies the fourth rank among exporters of
clothes to the European Union (EU). It ensures about 6 percent of
the European imports of clothes.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The Palestinian Ministry of Economy and Industry
will allocate 50 million U.S. dollars for the projects undertaken
by the governmental "Cities and Industrial Park Areas Authority"
already incorporated in the Palestinian development plan for the
coming three years (1999-2001).
</P>
<P>
Thursday's "Al Hayat" reported that Trade Minister Maher
Al-Masri said the money will be distributed among 14 industrial
parks, including 4 border parks adjacent to Israel and the
remaining 10 under Palestinian municipal rule.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that border industrial parks will get
19 million dollars, while 31 million dollars will go to the
municipality-related parks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
