<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JEDDAH -- The Islamic Bank President Ahmed Mohamed Ali has
announced that the bank has embarked on the establishment of a 1.5
billion-U.S. dollar infrastructure fund for related projects in
its 52 member states, "Al Hayat" reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sectors envisaged by the fund include electricity,
telecommunications, transport, natural resources, petrochemicals
and other infrastructure-related sectors.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has decided on a
comprehensive strategy to reform the National Electric Power
Company, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The company will be split into three separate divisions: the
first is in charge of power generation and assumes ownership of
all the company's assets; the second is in charge of distributing
power; the third is in charge of transmitting power.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The prices of all types of cars have recently declined
by 10 to 20 percent in Jordan, mainly due to devaluation of
currencies of some Asian countries and world economic recession,
the semi-official Jordan Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is fierce competition in saturated local
market, the paper quoted Hassan E`layyan, general manager of
South Korea's Hyundai Company in Jordan, as saying.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Administrative Council of Jordanian Exports
Development and Trade Centers Corporation decided to open a
trade center at the Jordanian Embassy in Algeria, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The center is expected to raise Jordanian export volume to
Algeria and provide information of the Algerian markets for
Jordanian businessmen, the news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
