<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Countries Join Hands in Combating Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) ended their two-day
meeting here Thursday after deciding to work together to revive
the economies hit by the ongoing Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said in a joint statement that they had discussed
a set of "bold measures" to restore investor confidence in the
region and facilitate economic recovery covering investments,
trade and services.
</P>
<P>
But the statement did not elaborate, saying only that these
measures, if approved by the governments of the ASEAN countries,
would be announced by the ASEAN heads of government at its sixth
summit in Hanoi, Vietnam, in December this year.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the ministers welcomed the decision of the
ASEAN finance ministers to establish an ASEAN surveillance
mechanism to prevent future financial crises similar to the
current one in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The surveillance process is also aimed at monitoring
developments in ASEAN member countries and in the international
economy that could affect individual ASEAN economies and the
region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
To avert the sharp decline of foreign investments into the
region, the ministers approved and signed the Framework Agreement
on ASEAN Investment Area (AIA) and established a ministerial-level
AIA council.
</P>
<P>
The AIA, to be established by the year 2010, will provide to
ASEAN, in a collective manner, and to the individual member
countries, greater benefits in attracting foreign direct
investments to revive the economies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministers also approved and signed the Protocol
on Notification Procedures that obliges member countries to give
advance notice 60 days prior to taking any actions that will
impair or nullify the benefits enjoyed by other member countries
from any ASEAN economic agreements.
</P>
<P>
During the gathering, the ministers also agreed to accelerate
the implementation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area by reducing the
tariffs of more products to zero percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
To promote greater intra-ASEAN trade and mitigate the impacts
of the financial crisis, six ASEAN member countries -- Indonesia,
Malaysia, Myanmar, Indonesia, the Philippines and Thailand --
agreed to use local currencies in regional trade during the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Govt Urges "Constructive" Cooperation From NLD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government Thursday
urged the country's opposition party, the National League for
Democracy (NLD), to contribute in a positive and meaningful way to
achieving a thriving economy and a stable multi-party democratic
system.
</P>
<P>
The official Information Sheet quoted Lt. Col. Hla Min, an
official at the Office of Strategic Studies of the Myanmar Defense
Ministry, as saying that "now is the time for responsible,
constructive cooperation, not whimsical and symbolic gestures
designed merely to attract attention."
</P>
<P>
Hla Min, who briefed foreign diplomats here Wednesday on the
current political situation in Myanmar, rapped the NLD for having
unilaterally rejected further meetings between the government and
the NLD. In August, Lt. Gen. Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the
Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, and NLD Chairman U
Aung Shwe met to discuss prospects of launching an era of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hla Min criticized the NLD for making the inclusion of the
party's general secretary Aung San Suu Kyi, whom the government
calls a "private citizen," a precondition for any further
meetings.
</P>
<P>
The government welcomes official meetings with legal
representatives of political parties, Hla Min said, pointing out
that an inclusion of a "private citizen" in such official meetings
is "inappropriate."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the regional economic crisis is still biting
with much work remaining ahead, and stressed the need to work
together to develop strong policies on economic development,
anti-narcotics, national security and the establishment of a
National Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"If political crisis leads to a crisis in national security,
then Myanmar's very existence is in danger with domestic armed
groups probably taking advantage of political confusion to split
the country into a number of mini-states," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The government has insisted on the exclusion of Aung San Suu
Kyi from dialogue between it and the NLD. The NLD, on the other
hand, sticks to its position that such dialogue must include her
attendance for being a key leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the NLD formed a 10-member Committee Representing
the Parliament Elected in the 1990 Multi-Party General Election
and set up a People's Parliament unilaterally after the party's
deadline for the parliament to be convened was ignored by the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
