<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,700 Drug Addicts Arrested in Singapore This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Central Narcotics Bureau
(CNB) of Singapore announced Thursday that its officers have
arrested more than 1,700 suspected hard-core drug addicts in 11
operations in the state this year.
</P>
<P>
The figure was released after the CNB rounded 94 people
suspected of drug offenses in island-wide raids Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among the detainees, 44 tested positive, the CNB said.
</P>
<P>
The CNB said the raids were mounted to hunt down recalcitrant
addicts who have relapsed.
</P>
<P>
Following the raids, the CNB said there are no longer any
so-called "black areas" in Singapore where drugs are openly bought
and sold in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's anti-drug law amendment took effect in July,
toughening penalties against hard-core drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, 49 hard-core addicts were sentenced to
imprisonment terms ranging from five to seven years in addition to
three to six strokes of the cane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Kicks off Presidential Election Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese cabinet kicked off the
presidential election process at its exceptional session on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Information Minister Bassem Al-Sabaa told
reporters that the cabinet has decided to draft a bill on amending
the constitution to pave the way for Emile Lahoud, commander of
the Lebanese Army, to stand for the election.
</P>
<P>
Under Lebanon's constitution, any senior public servant who
wants to run for the presidency must quit his or her post two
years prior to the election.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud was endorsed as the presidential candidate during a
summit between Lebanese President Alias Hrawi and Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad last Monday in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which is maintaining about 40,000 troops as
peacekeepers in Lebanon, agree to coordinate stances on key issues.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, 62, a close ally of Syria, was appointed as army
commander in 1989, just prior to the end of the country's 15-year
civil war.
</P>
<P>
He has gained popular support due to his accomplishments in
rebuilding the army into a cohesive and stabilizing force of the
country after its disintegration during the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
