<HEADLINE> U.S. to Mediate Turkish-Syrian Crisis, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk said here Thursday that Washington will
begin its mediation to defuse the Turkish-Syrian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa,
Indyk said Washington will exert efforts to "strike a compromise
between toning down the tension and taking into account the
Turkish apprehensions."
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Turkish side to be patient and advise Syria to
take the matter seriously," he added.
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Mideast neighbors Syria and Turkey have
deteriorated in recent weeks with Syria bridling at Turkey's
growing military links with Israel and Turkey threatening Damascus
for allegedly aiding Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Indyk called for "serious political dialog" to solve the issue,
saying that U.S. President Bill Clinton welcomes Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak's mediation.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak visited Turkey and Syria Tuesday to offer a set of
proposals to start a direct dialog for an immediate solution.
</P>
<P>
"Both Egypt and the U.S. believe the situation is quite serious
and that there is an urgent need to tone down the escalation in
order to deal with the real fears which haunt Turkey which is
extremely concerned with the activities of the outlawed Turkish
Kurdish rebels in Syria," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indyk is part of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's team
that flew to the region Tuesday to narrow Palestinian-Israeli
differences on a U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank in exchange for serious Palestinian crackdown
on terrorism. 
</P>
