<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Confusion and Division Grow Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Despite the fact that
NATO announced the beginning of a countdown to formally authorize
military intervention over Kosovo, confusion and division are
growing among Western countries over what to do next about what
they saw as emerging humanitarian catastrophe in Kosovo, Serbia's
province of mainly ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Outspoken threatening remarks by NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana, reported on Wednesday by French newspaper Le Monde, do not
agree with what was stated by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who said, on a visit to the Middle East, that no
consensus has been reached over a next step on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"No one is in a rush to use force" against the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia, James Rubin, U.S. State Department spokesman said
on the sidelines of Albright's Middle East tour, adding that no
one ever stated that NATO would definitely make a decision within
this week.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both Britain and the United States, which has
been promoting a NATO decision to take military action against
Serb target to force full compliance with U.N. resolutions,
stressed on Wednesday afternoon that no deadline had been set.
This was again contradictory to Solana's previous statement that
the military action would take place within days.
</P>
<P>
At present, military threats are co-existing with diplomatic
actions to seek a political solution. However, Western countries
have all good reasons to hesitate and disagree with others over
the use of force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led Western alliance has deep concerns over the legal
basis for military intervention in what Belgrade long claimed its
internal affairs. At the same time, Italy and Germany asked NATO
to seek a U.N. agreement before air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Resolution 1199 and a report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, explicitly or implicitly, gave no
green light for NATO to formally activate its military forces over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi called for more diplomacy
before reverting to force, saying air strikes would have to be
"legitimized" by the 185-member United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Italy, with major U.S. and NATO airbases at Aviano, Vicenza,
Villafranca and other locations, is a key element in finalized
NATO planning, if any, for air strikes against Yugoslav military
targets.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that if NATO bypasses the United Nations to
stage military action against Yugoslavia, it will constitute a
flare violation of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Russia, one of the five permanent members of
the Security Council with veto power, intensified its diplomacy
and insistence on foiling any intention at the Security Council to
okay military intervention against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian stance, together with concerted appeals for
peaceful solution in the international community, largely added to
the Western hesitation and division over the next step on Kosovo,
where ethnic Albanians have been battling with Serbs for
independence.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, which groups six nations including Russia,
announced the postponement of a meeting, originally scheduled for
Thursday in London. Such a move was interpreted by the world
community once again as the disagreement among powers over a next
step.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, many countries in the Yugoslavia region, known as
the powder keg in the Balkans, are multi-ethnic, any imprudent
action could have wider negative implications.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, which have been pressing for Belgrade's full
compliance with U.N. resolutions demanding an end to the reported
humanitarian catastrophe in the Serb province, actually do not
hope to see the independence of Kosovo, the goal of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
They rattled the threat of military action as a warning for
Belgrade to accept what West has offered. "The goal of our policy
is not to use force, if not necessary. The goal is to achieve
compliance with the international community (demands)," said U.S.
Richard Holbrooke, who failed to persuade Belgrade to give up its
position at the end of the third-round talks with Yugoslav
President Solobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Any military attacks on Yugoslavia would bring threats to the
security of NATO soldiers in neighboring Bosnia, who are
implementing a multinational mission of stabilization in the
war-torn region. Serbia, a dominant republic of Yugoslavia, said
that Serbs would respond to any possible NATO strikes with
retaliatory attacks on NATO soldiers in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Western countries are currently engaged in a series of
consultations over what to do next on Kosovo. Belgrade has
formally asked the Organization of European Security and
Cooperation to send a team to Kosovo in order to gather first-hand
information on the situation of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The return of 50,000 refugees and withdrawal of security forces
in Kosovo, reported by U.N. agencies, send a strong message to the
world that the international diplomatic efforts do not fail.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the unilateral use of force will not bring about a
fundamental settlement of the Kosovo issue, and it may, on the
contrary, reinforce the separatist and terrorist forces in the
region and intensify the tension in the Balkans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
