<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs to Hold Free Elections: British Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia needs to hold free and
fair general elections as a means to gain long-term stability, a
special emissary from British Prime Minister Tony Blair said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Free and fair elections are crucial to Indonesia's long-term
stability," Derek Fatchett, who is Minister of State for Foreign
and Commonwealth Affairs, said at the end of a two-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after meeting with President
B.J. Habibie, Fatchett said the holding of general elections was
one of the main topics of his discussion with the Indonesian
leader as well as with the Independent Election Monitoring
Committee, a non-governmental organization.
</P>
<P>
"I can announce today that we are also ready to give practical
assistance to help Indonesia in the political field, notably to
help it hold free and fair elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government and the House of Representative have
agreed that the general elections should be held in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said the British government welcomed the steps
President Habibie and his administration had already taken towards
the holding of free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
The human rights situation in Indonesia had improved and the
British government was closely cooperating with Indonesia's
National Commission on Human Rights in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said his government was strongly committed to helping
Indonesia achieve economic recovery and make changes toward
greater democracy.
</P>
<P>
The British government would also continue to assist Indonesia
in dealing with its economic problems through the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and other international channels, he
added.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Fatchett said, he also met Defense Minister
Gen. Wiranto and members of the National Commission on Human
Rights. 
</P>
