<HEADLINE> German Greens Insist on UN Mandate for Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Greens party, the most
likely junior partners in the new German government, stressed
Thursday that it would oppose any German participation in a
possible NATO military action in Kosovo without a U.N. resolution
approving the use of force.
</P>
<P>
In a position paper issued Thursday in Bonn, Greens' expert on
defense affairs, Angelika Beer, said her party would not give up
its demand for sufficient legal basis prior to any military
intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
She also called for more diplomatic efforts, including closer
cooperation with Russia, to defuse the rising tensions in the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
German commentators said that the pacifist Greens is facing a
major foreign policy test on the Kosovo issue at a time when it is
just trying to negotiate a workable alliance with the Social
Democratic Party (SPD) to form the next German government later
this month.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, which defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative
alliance in the general election on September 27, has said that it
supports the offer made by Kohl's government to provide 14 Tornado
jets for possible NATO air strikes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Guenther Verheugen, a SPD expert on foreign affairs who could
become defense minister in the new government, Thursday expressed
the belief that the existing U.N. Security Council resolution on
Kosovo has provided sufficient legal basis for a possible NATO
intervention.
</P>
<P>
However, any German participation in the NATO intervention must
be approved by the German Bundestag (lower house of parliament),
which has been virtually paralized during the transitional period
after the election.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move, Kohl, who acts as caretaker chancellor at
the moment, and Gerhard Schroeder, the incoming chancellor, held a
special meeting in Bonn Thursday for discussions on the Kosovo
situation.
</P>
<P>
The talks came just hours before Schroeder left for Washington
to meet U.S. president Bill Clinton. The Kosovo conflict is
expected to be one of the top issues on Schroeder's agenda.
</P>
</TEXT>
