<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Killed in Clashes With Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian was killed on
Thursday during the clashes between Palestinian protesters and
Israeli soldiers in the West Bank city of Hebron, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The clashes erupted as dozens of Palestinians threw stones at
Israeli soldiers guarding Jewish enclaves in the
Israeli-controlled downtown sector of Hebron. And the soldiers
responded with rubber-coated bullets.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Palestinian youth was hit on the head by a
rubber bullet and died in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
A number of other Palestinians were injured in the clashes,
including a cameraman who was working for the Agence France-Presse
news agency.
</P>
<P>
The cameraman, Hussam Abu Alan, was also hit by a rubber
bullet on his head. He was reportedly wounded seriously but
not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
Following the clashes, Yigal Sharon, top Israeli army
commander in Hebron, said in a statement that when troops fired
rubber bullets at stone throwers, they were not aware that a
photographer was among them.
</P>
<P>
He held Palestinian police responsible for the violence,
noting that they had done nothing to restrain the stone throwers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinians in Hebron launched a general strike on
Thursday in protest against the eight-day blockade and curfew
imposed by Israeli troops on the city.
</P>
<P>
Israel lifted the closure Thursday morning, which had
barred Palestinians from entering and leaving the city.
</P>
<P>
But the curfew remains in effect, which confines some 30,000
Palestinians living in the Israeli-controlled city center to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
The blockade and curfew were imposed by Israeli troops last
Wednesday after some 20 Israeli soldiers and Palestinian
civilians were wounded in a hand grenade attack in the downtown
area of the city.
</P>
<P>
Palestine National Liberation Movement (Al Fatah) distributed a
leaflet on Tuesday, calling for a general strike on Thursday and
demonstrations on Friday in Hebron unless the blockade and curfew
were lifted.
</P>
<P>
About 450 settlers live in a number of enclaves in
downtown Hebron, surrounded by about 130,000 Palestinians and
protected by large numbers of Israeli soldiers and police.
</P>
</TEXT>
