Chretien.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council consists of five permanent members--Britain,
China, France, Russia and the United States-- and ten elected members
whose seats are allocated among five regional groups and who serve
two-year terms each. Canada and the netherlands were elected Thursday
to the two available seats in the Western Europe and Others Group. The
other new members elected Thursday were Argentina, Malaysia and
Namibia.  
