<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Optimistic About Iran-Afghan Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi expressed optimism here Thursday night
that the existing tension between Iran and the Taliban would be
peacefully resolved.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the media upon his arrival from Tehran on the second
leg of his peace mission, Brahimi said the situation is very grave
and should be addressed immediately.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, accompanied by Assistant Secretary General Ibrahim
Bakara of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, said: "We
have no time to lose. There is a crisis, the crisis needs to be
addressed as soon as possible. It needs to be addressed tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said his talks with Pakistani officials and the Taliban
begin in Islamabad Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Six Plus Two (Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors plus
the U.S. and Russia) group at its recent meeting in New York
decided to send Brahimi to the region amidst growing tension
between Iran and Afghanistan over the killing of Iranian personnel
in Mazar-i-Shafir early August.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you that I have come here reasonably optimistic.
There is a good chance to make progress and move away from the
dangers of the situation towards a better and satisfactory
resolution of the problem," Brahimi said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi described his talks with Iranian leaders as highly
successful and said Iranian leaders expressed their commitment to
solve the problem through diplomatic and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
He said he has received an invitation from the Afghan Taliban
to visit Afghanistan but "due to our security concerns, I would
not be able to go to Afghanistan until these concerns are
removed."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Office spokesman said last Saturday that
Brahimi's mission to the region will remain incomplete unless he
visits Afghanistan. Taliban leader Mulla Muhammad Rabbani has sent
a letter to Brahimi inviting him to Afghanistan for talks with
Taliban leaders.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about the border clash between Iran
and the Taliban, Brahimi said: "This has been exaggerated by the
press as usual and that it will be contained." 
</P>
</TEXT>
