<HEADLINE> S. African Gold, Foreign Assets Drop in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's gold and
foreign assets fell 2.18 billion Rand (363 million U.S. Dollars)
in September to about 30.50 billion Rand (5.08 billion Dollars),
the South African Reserve Bank (SARB) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement detailing its assets and liabilities, the SARB
said gold reserves for the month declined 533.36 million Rand
(88.89 million Dollars) to 6.16 billion Rand (1.02 billion
Dollars), while foreign assets dipped 1.65 billion Rand (275
million Dollars) to 24.36 billion Rand (four billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Similarly, notes and coins in circulation fell by 19.13
million Rand (3.18 million Dollars) to 23.31 billion Rand (3.89
billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government deposits rose 274.61 million Rand (45.7
million Dollars) while bank deposit went up 246.42 million Rand
(41 million Dollars) to 7.71 billion Rand (1.28 billion Dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
