<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Relieved as Roadblocks in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 8 (Xinhua) -- People in the Somali capital
and the business community of southern Somalia sighed with relief
Thursday after the roadblocks between Mogadishu and Afgoie town,
30 km south of Mogadishu, have been removed.
</P>
<P>
About a hundred heavily armed militiamen led by Hussein Ali
Weheliye (Erfo), the security chief of Afgoie town, launched an
operation at 4:00 a.m. local time Thursday to fight against
illegal roadblocks set along the Afgoie road.
</P>
<P>
According to Erfo, the operation which lasted a few hours
ended with 25 illegal roadblocks dismantled. The militiamen at
the illegal roadblocks were most probably notified by their
fellow men earlier Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"We met no resistance at any point and therefore arrested no
one in connection with the roadblocks," said Erfo.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still five more checkpoints at the K-7
strong point and its surrounding areas manned by militiamen loyal
to faction leader Osman Ali Atto, who continue demanding lorries
and public buses for extortion money.
</P>
<P>
Erfo said his men will not abandon the road. Meanwhile, he
will assign permanently two battle wagons and its infantry
militiamen to patrol the road against the erection of new
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
A bus driver who arrived on the Afgoie road Thursday said he
spent less than an hour after paying the militiamen at the
remaining roadblocks 50,000 Somali Shillings (about 6.25 U.S.
Dollars) on his trip to Mogadishu. Earlier, he had to spend 15
times as much.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the security chief and his men demolished eight
illegal roadblocks along the road between Afgoie town and
Ballidogle airport, 90 km south of the capital. During the
operation ten militiamen were rounded up for manning the illegal
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
Before the two operations, it took the drivers more than six
hours to make 30 km between Mogadishu and Afgoie town due to the
innumerable roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the operations will revive the hope of
hundreds of lorry and bus owners who have got out of the business
just for the sake of those roadblocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
