<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa's Economy to Grow by 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa's economy is
likely to grow by three percent in 1998 if the weather
conditions, maintenance of peace and political stability and
economic environment are favorable, a report said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The estimated growth rate would be determined by the above
mentioned conditions, said the report of the Intergovernmental
Committee of Experts for Southern Africa (ICE) released at the
end of the ICE's fifth meeting held from October 5 to 8.
</P>
<P>
While reviewing the economic and social conditions in the
sub-region, the report noted although overall GDP growth rate in
1997 was positive at 2.4 percent, it was, nonetheless, 20 percent
lower than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the performance varied among countries and
between economic sectors, saying that the growth in agricultural
production had declined to 6.8 percent in 1997 from 10.3 percent
in 1996, owing mostly to the adverse El Nino phenomenon that
persisted in the sub-region throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
And the performance of the mining sector in 1997 was rather
poor, in particularly in the mineral and metal subsector due to
lower demand in the world market.
</P>
<P>
There were, however, improved performance and developments
registered in the transport and communications sector, which is
particularly reflected in the upgrading of roads, ports and
railways infrastructure as well as improved telecommunications
services in the sub-region, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As far as the debt problem, which hinders the sub-region's
economic development, is concerned, the report criticized the
initiatives now pursued to alleviate it and even the recently
launched Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative as
"inadequate".
</P>
<P>
"The agony of the debt problem should be ended," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
It urged the international community to work out a
"comprehensive" solution to end the debt problem and carry out a
"far-reaching" reform of the international financial system and
institutions as well as a "fundamental" reform of the
international assistance process itself.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, whose theme is "Cultivating Effective
Partnership in Southern Africa - Development is everybody's
business", attracted about 80 delegates from Botswana, Malawi,
Namibia, South Africa, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Regional bodies such as the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and the
U.N. agencies in Zambia were also represented at the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
