<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows Not to Give in to U.S. Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu declared Thursday that he will not give in to
U.S. pressure during the scheduled U.S. summit meeting next week,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks during a meeting with leaders of the
National Religious Party (NRP), a far-right partner in his
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The NRP requested the convening of the meeting to warn
Netanyahu not to make concessions under U.S. pressure at the
summit with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser
Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be held at the Wye Plantation in Maryland,
where Israeli and Syrian negotiators met for the first
face-to-face talks three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The NRP has threatened to topple the government if Netanyahu
agrees to hand over 13 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians, but it holds now that the most important question is
whether Israel will get security guarantee, especially for the
Jewish settlements, when it relinquishes part of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Netanyahu also agreed to the NRP request at
the meeting that he convene a special cabinet session next
Tuesday to brief the ministers on his position at the coming
U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
NRP cabinet minister Shaul Yhalom said that Netanyahu made
clear at the meeting that he will not surrender to any pressure
at the summit. He said the prime minister promised to NRP leaders
that he will declare at the special cabinet session that Israel
will withdraw from only 1 percent of the West Bank in the third
phases of further pullback.
</P>
<P>
Substantial progress was made on various issues in the
trilateral talks Wednesday between Netanyahu, Arafat and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the Israel-Gaza
border, but sources close to the talks said the timetable and thescope of the th
ird withdrawal is among the problems remaining
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that Washington has reached understandings
with Israel over the third stage of further Israeli withdrawal,
but the PNA is demanding a larger scope.
</P>
<P>
In another effort to seek support from within his government,
Netanyahu convened his "kitchen cabinet" earlier Thursday to
brief the other three members -- Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, and
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky -- on his talks with
Arafat Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Netanyahu has invited the three ministers to
go with him for the U.S. summit. NRP leaders demanded that another
NRP minister, Yitzhak Levy, be also invited to the U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross continued his
mediation in the region Thursday, holding three hours of talks
with the Israeli-Palestinian joint committees to discuss interim
issues, especially the opening of the Palestinian airport in
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The airport has been a contentious point between the two sides
for the past 18 months, mainly due to Israeli security
concerns. U.S. officials have said that Ross will try to wrap up
an understanding on the issue before he leaves the region Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mordechai held a working session in Tel Aviv with
George Tenet, head of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA),
on security issues, mainly the Israeli demand that the PNA take
measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The CIA is trying to bring the two sides closer for an
understanding on security cooperation, which some said is also
one of the main problems facing the U.S. summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
