<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF/World Bank Meetings Ends with Calls for End of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Finance officials from 182
nations ended a week of discussions here Thursday with a broad
blueprint for an approach needed to end the worst global economic
crisis in a half century.
</P>
<P>
At the annual International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank
meeting, the finance ministers and central bank governors from the
world widely discussed the worsening global financial turmoil and
a world recession and worked out strategies to deal with them,
focusing on strengthened international financial architecture and
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone agrees there is a way out of the crisis. It is an
uphill way, but it is there," IMF Managing Director Michael
Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus predicted that the IMF, which has put together 137
billion dollars in bailout packages for nations leveled by market
turmoil so far, would soon have an additional 90 billion dollars
in resources.
</P>
<P>
But that requires a U.S. Congress approval of 18 billion dollars
American share of that amount.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus expressed optimistic over the situation and said "an
extensive agenda awaits us in moving toward a more durable
international monetary system."
</P>
<P>
World Bank President James Wolfensohn also said the his agency
and IMF were working closely together and "have a time-tested
approach to face this crisis and any others that come down the
line."
</P>
<P>
As one of the actions, the IMF immediately announced it was
closer to agreement with Brazil on an international package to
support the Latin American nation to overcome its financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement issued on behalf of the IMF and Brazil said
"discussions will continue in the days ahead, with the aim of
reaching agreement soon" on a detailed economic reform program
that could receive the financial support of the IMF and other
lenders.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that Brazil would get a total of 30 billion
billion U.S. dollars or more as the IMF tries to stop a financial
contagion that has already leveled a number of Asian countries and
Russia from spreading to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The United States worried that if the financial turmoil topples
the biggest economy in Latin America it could spread to other
nations in the region, which absorb nearly 20 percent of U.S.
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
