<HEADLINE> Reppas: Greece Not to Withdraw Diplomatic Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- There was no need for Greece to
issue a travel advisory for Yugoslavia or withdraw its diplomatic
mission from Belgrade, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said that Greek diplomatic
authorities remained in Yugoslavia and were ready to provide any
assistance to Greeks who choose not to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece did not consider it useful to take any
other decision.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government was now watching the developments closely
in Kosovo and was firm in its position that every effort should be
made for a peaceful solution to the crisis, Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis had contacts with other European leaders on the
developments in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Greece, unlike other European Union countries, has repeatedly
voiced its opposition to any possible NATO military intervention
in Kosovo, saying that all diplomatic and political approaches had
yet to be exhausted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
