<HEADLINE> Two Top Pakistani Army Generals Go on Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Two top three-star generals of
the Pakistani Army went home Thursday following the appointment of
Gen. Pervez Musharaf as new chief of the Army Staff, the News
Network International reported, quoting defense sources.
</P>
<P>
Without confirming their resignation, an officer from the Inter
Service Public Relations (ISPR) said Chief of General Staff Lt.
Gen. Ali Kuli Khan and Quarter Master General Lt. Gen. Malik
Khalid Nawaz went on leave effective on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
Committee and Chief of the Army Staff (COAS) Gen. Jehangir Karamat
resigned from his office Wednesday night, just two days after his
criticism of the policies of the present government. The ISPR also
confirmed that during a meeting of the new chief of the Army Staff
with the principal staff officers at General Headquarters, both
Kuli Khan and Khalid Nawaz were absent.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, Kuli Khan, the most senior officer
in line after Gen. Karamat, was supposed to get the job of COAS.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an official from the Ministry of Defense confirmed
that the two generals had gone on leave.
</P>
<P>
"So far no resignation has been submitted by the two," the
official added.
</P>
<P>
The tenures of Lt. Gen. Ali Kuli Khan and Lt. Gen. Khalid Nawaz
are to expire early next year.
</P>
<P>
The report also quoted a retired army general as saying that
the two would tender their resignations in a couple of days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
