<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Army Chief Quits Amid Row With Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- To the surprise of many,
Pakistan's powerful army chief, Gen. Jehangir Karamat, resigned
Wednesday from his job, three months before his three-year tenure
expires.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in Pakistan's history that an army chief
resigned after a row with the government over how the country
should be run.
</P>
<P>
Karamat's unexpected resignation followed his proposal on
Monday to establish a national security council to
institutionalize the national decision-making system.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who was reportedly annoyed by the
proposal floated by Karamat at the Pakistan Naval War College in
Lahore, has accepted Karamat's resignation and appointed Lt. Gen.
Pervez Musharaf as the new army chief.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the proposed national security council
would give the influential Pakistani army a greater say in
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
Karamat cited Pakistan's fledgling economy, spiraling sectarian
and ethnic violence and growing frustration in the three smaller
provinces as the main reasons for him to suggest establishing a
national security council.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions during his annual address at the
Pakistan Naval War College in Lahore Monday, Karamat said unlike
countries with economic potential, Pakistan "could not afford the
destabilizing effects of polarization, vendettas and insecurity
driven expedient policies."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan should now focus on the economy, deal with its
relations with foreign countries in a better way, and stabilize
the internal situation, especially that in Sindh province.
</P>
<P>
Karamat said that could be done only by establishing a
structurally tiered system with clear responsibility at each
level.
</P>
<P>
A national security council or committee at the apex would
institutionalize decision-making if it was backed by a team of
credible advisors and a think-tank of experts, said Karamat.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition parties hailed Karamat's proposal which
sent a clear signal to the government of the army's discontent
over certain policies and the general situation in the country.
The opposition termed Karamat's proposal "the final warning" to
the government.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that it was the first time that Karamat,
who assumed office in January 1996, has suggested direct army
involvement in policy decisions through a national security
council.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, dogged by
economic turmoil and bitter opposition to a proposed
constitutional amendment which would create a new Islamic order in
the country, has yet to make official comment on Karamat's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports Thursday, the resignation of Karamat
and appointment of Musharaf as the new Army Chief came after a
meeting Wednesday morning between Prime Minister Sharif and
Karamat. The meeting was described as "far from amicable" by
informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Karamat said later in his letter to Sharif that "unnecessary
debate" has started on his proposal for the establishment of a
national security council, so he decided to step down so that "a
healthy tradition is set for future."
</P>
<P>
He also told the News, an English daily in the country, that he
resigned "due to the controversy sparked over my statement two
days back."
</P>
<P>
He said he sought early retirement because he felt distressed
by the "unnecessary debate" over his proposals which he made in
good faith and with sincerity of purpose.
</P>
<P>
While there is support for Karamat's proposal from different
sections of the country, the government seems to be livid at his
statement which some say was a "public charge-sheet" against Prime
Minister Sharif and his style of governance.
</P>
<P>
While the armed forces remain the most powerful institution in
Pakistan, the last 10 years have seen their overt role in shaping
politics slowly diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Fearing government-military confrontation, Pakistan's former
army generals have criticized Sharif over Karamat's resignation.
</P>
<P>
"The conduct of the government would escalate the crises being
faced by the PML (Pakistan Muslim League)," retired Lt. Gen. Faiz
Ali Chishti said.
</P>
<P>
Chishti said the recent statement of Gen. Karamat was issued
with the consensus of the three services. "Ignoring the feeling of
the Armed Forces will push the country towards a new crises," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It remains to be seen how the government would respond to
Karamat's proposal and deal its relations with the army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
