<HEADLINE> Israeli Currency Depreciates Against Dollar Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The exchange rate of Israel's
currency shekel dropped on Thursday to 4.31 to one U.S. dollar,
devaluing by more than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
A report of Israel Radio said the representative rate of the
Bank of Israel closed at a new record low in the day.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this month, the shekel has fallen more
than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation has raised speculations over whether the
central bank should intervene in the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Following the latest plunge, Israel's opposition Labor Party
called on the government to take immediate measures against the
depreciation, noting that the plunge would endanger the economy.
</P>
<P>
There are no reports about the reaction of the government.
</P>
<P>
But Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman said on Wednesday that
"what is happening now to the shekel is a reflection of what is
happening to the global economy."
</P>
<P>
He denied that the Israeli financial market is in crisis,
calling on people to refrain from going panic.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts said the negative atmosphere on
international markets, rather than anything happening in Israel,
is the main reason for the recent devaluation of the shekel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
