<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Business Confidence Continues to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's business
confidence index dropped 1.8 points last month, the fifth
consecutive month of recorded decline, Business Day paper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The business index dived 5.7, two and 4.1 points respectively
in the previous three months, according to figures from the South
African Chamber of Business (Sacob).
</P>
<P>
Sacob said Wednesday the further slippage in the business mood
last month was mainly the result of the renewed instability in
global financial markets and the negative implications this had
on emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Complicating the matter were domestic weaknesses, such as
strikes and the balance of payments, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa remained resilient compared with other
emerging markets and the country soon could see a return in
investor confidence, Sacob said.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was based on solid ratings of South Africa by
international ratings agencies and the positive influence this
had on financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Moody's Investor Service, a leading international rating
agency, recently gave a better investment grade rating to South
Africa which put the country before most other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Despite recent volatilities in the world markets which hit
South Africa, Sacob said there was a possibility of an interest
rate cut before the end of this year, especially in the light of
a more stable currency.
</P>
<P>
The South African Rand strengthened to 5.73 Rand to the U.S.
Dollar Wednesday, its highest level since July, largely owing to
the Dollar's sharp falls on international currency markets.
</P>
<P>
South African Reserve Bank deputy governor James Cross said
Wednesday that hedge funds were starting to leave the country and
this would help the Rand to strengthen and facilitate an
environment in which interest rates could ease.
</P>
<P>
Sacob forecast a 0.5 percent economic growth for the country
this year, which is far below the government target of two
percent but clearly away from the general fears of a recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
