<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Impose Higher Taxes to Curb Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Thursday stressed the importance of agriculture
and warned to impose higher taxes on imports of farm products.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who was touring the northern region of Arusha, said
that wheat produced locally lacked market while some businessmen
imported wheat and sold at much lower prices.
</P>
<P>
"We'll in that case be forced to increase tax on such and
other products threatening our local markets," the president
warned.
</P>
<P>
He said solutions to the problems should be found so that the
government could protect domestic products and secure income of
farmers, according to reports reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing government officials, members of parliament,
magistrates, and regional leaders of opposition parties, Mkapa
said time has been ripe for Tanzania to review problems facing
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said the prices of farm products are so low that even
production costs cannot be recovered, citing an example that in
the eastern region of Tanga a liter of milk sells at only 150
Shillings (675 Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar).
</P>
<P>
"The crusade against poverty will not succeed if we don't
review problems facing farmers and livestock keepers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the backbone of the country's economy, as it
comprises 55 percent of the national income and 80 percent of the
country's population are agriculture-oriented, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The president also calls for the protection of agriculture and
a rapid increase in its output so that people could live a better
life. 
</P>
