<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Turkey, Syria to Solve Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Thursday expressed deep
concern over the on-going tensions between Turkey and Syria,
urging Turkey to solve its differences with Syria through dialog.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Cabinet after a meeting chaired by President Saddam
Huusein expressed its concern over the irresponsible statements
made by some Turkish officials, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that any harm inflicted upon any Arab country is
harm on the Arab nation and Turkish people alike as well as on
good neighborly relations and Turkish-Arab interests.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, a spokesman for the Iraqi National Assembly,
or parliament, called on Arab people, parliaments and Arab
Parliamentary Union to show solidarity and unify their position
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reportedly massed troops backed by tanks and heavy
artillery along its border with Syria, sparking fear of a military
conflict between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have long been at odds over issues including
the alleged Syrian support for Turkey's Kurdish rebels, Turkey's
close military cooperation with Israel and water sharing.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials have accused Syria of sheltering its
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting since
1984 for autonomy in southeast Turkey, and threatened to wipe out
Kurdish bases in Syria. Syria has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
And Syria has accused Turkey of forming a military alliance
with Israel, which it said endangers Arab security, and building a
string of dams on the Euphrates River that could reduce Syria's
water supply.
</P>
<P>
Some Islamic countries, including Egypt and Iran, call for
political dialog to solve the Turkish-Syrian tensions.
</P>
</TEXT>
