<HEADLINE> Lesotho Govt to Dismiss Dissident Public Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government
Thursday threatened to dismiss public servants who had been
actively involved in opposition protests in the country's recent
political crisis, South African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a simple matter because these people have violated
the provisions of Lesotho's public service act which prohibits
government employees to actively participate in politics," SAPA
quoted Lesotho Foreign Minister Tom Thabane as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said government ministers had been ordered to convene
urgent meetings with their departmental staff to convey a message
that the culprits should resign or they would be forced out.
</P>
<P>
This means that Lesotho's estimated 10,000 public servants
could be reduced by half as early as next week, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Thabane said some government employees had used government
resources to further the objectives and aims of opposition
parties. Some employees had allegedly been involved in the
hijacking of government vehicles which were used to ferry
opposition supporters to various parts of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted unnamed analysts as saying that the move of the
government would not augur well for Lesotho's current situation.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties said it would be unconstitutional for the
move to expel employees because of their political affiliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
