<HEADLINE> S. Africa Loses Half Million Jobs in 4 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's overall
labor market shed 500,000 jobs over the past four years,
Statistics South Africa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said in a report that 19 percent of women and 28 percent of
men were jobless in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report found that 29 percent of blacks, 16 percent of
coloreds, 10 percent of Indians and four percent of whites were
without jobs.
</P>
<P>
It said the trade and financial sectors were the only ones to
gain jobs, while the mining, manufacturing, community services,
electricity, construction and transport fields all lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
The number of jobs in the agricultural sector declined from
1.4 million in 1994 to 637,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report found that race mattered in finding a job. One in
Every three black women were unemployed, compared to one in every
30 white men.
</P>
<P>
It also found that the jobless rate in rural areas was higher
than urban areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
