<HEADLINE> U.S. Hints More Missile Attacks Against Terrorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A top U.S. official suggested
on Thursday that further U.S. missile attacks against the
Afghanistan operations of Islamic extremist Osama bin Laden are
possible.
</P>
<P>
"We will take those actions we believe are necessary," Karl F.
Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for south Asian affairs,
told Congress.
</P>
<P>
"They consider that Mr. Osama bin Ladin is a guest.... We
believe that this man is not a guest, that he is a murderer and a
terrorist," Inderfurth said.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth also expressed concern over recent border clashes
between Taliban forces and Iran, but said he doubted the recent
massing of Iranian troops along its northeastern border signaled a
war between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is that the purpose of these exercises has been to
intimidate, not to necessarily presage an Iranian attack inside
Afghanistan," he told the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
near eastern and south Asian affairs.
</P>
<P>
On August 20, U.S. fired cruise missile against a purported
terrorist training camp in Afghanistan and other missiles at the
Al Shifa pharmaceutical factory in Khartoum, Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. launches the similar strikes, Inderfurth
said, "Those options are clearly available to us."
</P>
<P>
The attack in Afghanistan sent "a powerful message that
terrorists cannot find safe haven, even in nations that harbor
them," he added, calling Afghanistan "a vipers nest of terrorist
training."
</P>
<P>
"So, this must be dealt with, and the Taliban must understand
that its providing safe haven does make them complicity in the
activities that are conducted by the terrorists themselves,"
Inderfurth said.
</P>
<P>
"Our message is simple: Osama bin Laden, an international
terrorist leader still operating from Afghanistan, must be brought
to justice, and Afghanistan must stop being a terrorist base," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has linked bin Laden to the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa. Hundreds were killed and wounded
during the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
