<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Crash after Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- European share prices crashed
Thursday in the wake of the dollar, which has fallen sharply amid
persistent fears for the growth prospects of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate cut in Britain failed to give the London
stock market a much needed boost as the market slid downwards
amidst fears of a global recession.
</P>
<P>
The stock market dived to its lowest level this year after the
Bank of England cut interest rates by 0.25 percent, less than many
in the financial City would have liked.
</P>
<P>
As the market stumbled its way into the afternoon session, it
dropped to a day low of 4,599.2, down 229.7. But it managed a
half-hearted fight-back and closed the day down 130.0 at 4,698.9.
</P>
<P>
Financial organizations were amongst the biggest losers with
Prudential Corporation down 75p at 638p, Sun Life &AMP; Provincial
down 37p at 487p and CGU down 27.5p to 835p. Also, exporters led
the leading index down as the pound rebounded on the previous
session's heavy falls.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Dax index plummeted 4.98 percent in
electronic trading to close at 3,861.89 points. Among Germany's
most depressed shares was Bavarian car maker, hit by both the
dollar and the pound.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the bourse kept company with other European stock
markets in their plunge, as the Cac 40 index finished down 4.45
percent at 2,959.97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
