<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada To Ban Split-Run U.S. Magazines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada is to discuss a new
legislation to protect its national magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
Bill C-55, tabled by Heritage Minister Sheila Copps on
Thursday, would introduce a ban on Canadian editions of foreign
publications.
</P>
<P>
Once the new law is endorsed, fines of up to 250,000 Canadian
dollars (162,500 U.S. dollars) will be levied against U.S.
magazine publishers who solicit Canadian advertising for split
runs, in which foreign content is matched with Canadian
advertising.
</P>
<P>
Jay Ziegler, a spokesman for U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky, said the new regulation was potentially
discriminating, adding that the U.S. may launch a complaint at the
World Trade Organization or under the North American Free Trade
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to win this fight because it's an important fight
for Canada," said Copps.
</P>
<P>
"This is not just about Canadian magazines, it's about
countries' capacities to protect and to promote their own
culture," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian magazine industry endorsed the legislation.
</P>
<P>
"It's very good news," said Francois de Gaspe Beaubien,
president of the Canadian Magazine Publishers Association.
</P>
<P>
"American publishers, the foreign publishers, will not be able
to come in and undercut and skim the advertising service market in
Canada," he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign magazines account for 50 percent of yearly Canadian
magazine sales, or 350 million Canadian dollars (227 million
U.S. dollars), and 80 percent of newsstand space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
