<HEADLINE> Drug Problems Hit Italian Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian drug problem could hit
Turin's chances to host the 2006 Winter Olympic Games, the bid
organizers said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Inspectors from the International Olympic Committee will be in
Turin for three days next week to evaluate the city's bid.
</P>
<P>
But the resignation of the Italy's Olympic Committee (CONI)
president Mario Pescante over the dope-testing fiasco in soccer,
and the fact that the entire remaining CONI leadership could be
disbanded at any moment by Deputy Prime Minister Walter Veltroni,
will not be lost on the IOC officials.
</P>
<P>
The latest blow to Italy's already battered image came on
Wednesday, when the IOC closed down the CONI-approved laboratory
at Acqua Acetosa which has been at the centre of the doping
scandal.
</P>
<P>
The IOC will make it decision at a meeting in Seoul on June 19
next year.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Turin and Sion, the other four candidates for the
Games are Helsinki (Finland) in a joint bid with Lillehammer
(Norway), Zakopane (Poland), Poprad Tatry (Slovakia) and
Klagenfurt (Austria). 
</P>
