<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Grows Despite Bad Weather: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has said Uganda's economy has grown very well in spite
of adverse weather conditions last year.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Friday afternoon when addressing the
nation in a big function here marking the 36th anniversary of the
country's independence.
</P>
<P>
"This year, in spite of the adverse weather conditions which
we experienced and a slowdown in the three high growth
sub-sectors in recent years, namely, manufacturing, electricity
and construction, we have still been able to achieve a growth
rate of 5.5 percent," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"This is lower than the average of 6.5 percent which we've got
accustomed to in the last 10 years, but it's still high even by
world standards," he added.
</P>
<P>
The annual headline inflation stood at a negative 2.4 percent
in August and the overall balance of payment has improved
recently compared with past years.
</P>
<P>
The gross international reserves have risen to a new high,
equivalent to five months of imports and services, much more than
in 1986 to 1987 when the reserves could only cover three weeks of
imports and services, Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni attributed the economic growth maily to good products
management, freeing of exchange rates and liberalization of
trade.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the liberalization of trade, more traditional
crops were exported. Production of coffee, he said, went up from
2.5 million bags per annum to 4.5 million bags. 
</P>
</TEXT>
