<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Agrees to Revise Milan Airline Traffic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Friday that Italy had agreed to revise its traffic redistribution
plan for Milan's two airports.
</P>
<P>
The revised plan would ensure a non-discriminatory and
proportionate redistribution of airline traffic between the Linate
and Malpensa airports.
</P>
<P>
"The new rules will ensure effective competition and they will
work in favor of passengers," said the European Transport
Commissioner Neil Kinnock.
</P>
<P>
The main elements of the agreement are expected to be
incorporated into an Italian government decree regarding the
airline traffic distribution in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government decided last November to redistribute
airline traffic between Milan's existing airport Linate and the
new airport Malpensa 2000 which is expected to start operating on
October 25.
</P>
<P>
Under that resolution, all carriers with more than two million
passengers a year will continue to fly in and out of the
easily-accessible Linate while other flights will have to fly in
and out of Malpensa, 53 kilometers from Milan, which still lacks
ground transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union (EU), ruled on September 16 that Italy's airline
share-out plan is incompatible with EU law on fair competition.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, nine European carriers including British
Airways, Iberia, TAP, Sabena, Lufthansa, Air France, Olympic,
Austria Airlines and SAS complained to the commission that the
share-out plan was discriminatory and disproportionate.
</P>
<P>
They argued that due to the insufficient road and rail links
between Milan and Malpensa, passengers would continue to choose to
fly Italy's national carrier Alitalia out of Linate, which is
close to Milan town center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
