<HEADLINE> EU, Japan to Discuss Economic Development in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Japan will hold a meeting focusing on economic development in both
Asia and Japan, EU officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The importance of the EU-Japan cooperation in face of the world
financial problems will be discussed at the meeting in Tokyo for
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among those who will attend are European Commission
Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan, European Commissioners Martin
Bangemann and Anita Gradin, and Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Koumura.
</P>
<P>
Discussions will center on proposals to kick-start the Japanese
economy as a vital step toward Asian economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation, however, will also raise the issue of bad
debts in the Japanese financial system, plans for further fiscal
stimulus and progress toward deregulation and structural reform.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union is expected to give Japan a list of some
200 deregulation proposals during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Japanese relationship is hailed as having great
significance in light of the fact that they share over 45 percent
of the world's total gross national product.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relationship was forged in 1991 through a
Japan-European Community declaration. The European Community later
developed into the European Union in 1993. 
</P>
