<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Corrupt Official Expelled From Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of China
(CPC) recently expelled Yu Fei, former vice chairman of the
Guangdong Provincial People's Congress Standing Committee for
corruption centered on abuse of power for personal gain.
</P>
<P>
Yu used the power of his position to help a company operated by
his daughters earn profits of 28 million yuan from the illegal
transfer of land-use rights.
</P>
<P>
Yu's daughters and a son-in-law formed the Hong Kong Decheng
Company in 1992, but failed to obtain registration to buy, sell or
transfer land.
</P>
<P>
Yu convinced various departments to sell 220 hectares of land
in Huizhou near Daya Bay to the provincial economic and technology
cooperation office in 1991-1992.
</P>
<P>
The transaction was, in fact, nothing more than a front and the
Decheng Co. purchased the land at the exorbitantly low price of
180 yuan per square meter.
</P>
<P>
Yu later abused his power even further by forcing the local
government to acquire the company's land-use rights at 380 yuan
per square meter.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Chunqing, spokesman for the CPC Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection, said that Yu's actions not only caused
losses which harmed the nation and diluted the benefits of Chinese
citizens.
</P>
<P>
"Yu engaged in serious violations of Party discipline," said
Yuan. He urged Chinese officials to steadfastly avoid corruption
and refrain from engaging in actions for personal of family gain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
