<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:00GMT, October 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- U.N. Secretary General's Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi held talks here Friday with Pakistani
officials headed by Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, it was stressed that generous humanitarian
assistance was urgently required not only for the reconstruction
of Afghanistan but also to facilitate the return of Afghan
refugees, according to a press release issued by the Foreign
Office Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, assistance was needed for crop substitution in order
to eliminate the cultivation of poppy, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived here Thursday night from Tehran together
with Assistant Secretary General of the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) Ibrahim Bakr. (Pakistan-UN Envoy)
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO and Russia agreed Friday to support diplomatic
efforts to seek a solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a special meeting at ambassadorial
level of the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council (PJC).
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors from NATO and Russia exchanged information and
views on the situation in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the meeting said both NATO and Russia
had reiterated their deep concern about the serious humanitarian
crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also stressed the need to see immediate, full and
irreversible compliance with the United Nations Security Council
resolutions, which have demanded Yugoslavia withdraw its forces
from Kosovo and end its military action against the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The special PJC meeting was held in the wake of Thursday's
three-hour Contact Group meeting in London, where the foreign
ministers of the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy
and Russia met to prescribe a list of six demands for Belgrade.
(NATO-Russia-Kosovo)
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro Friday accepted
the resignation of Prime Minister Romano Prodi and asked him to
form a caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
A statement from Scalfaro's office said "the president asked
the outgoing government to stay in office in a caretaker
capacity".
</P>
<P>
Prodi, appointed on May 16, 1996, at the head of the cabinet,
lost a confidence vote in the lower house of parliament by one
vote earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Deputies rejected a confidence vote in Prodi's government by
313 votes to 312. (Italy-Resignation)
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Friday
named Ariel Sharon, a prominent hardliner in the cabinet, as the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
In a news conference hold in Prime Minister Office in
Jerusalem, Netanyahu said that Sharon will take the portfolio of
foreign minister next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharon will continue to be the minister of national
infrastructure for another three months.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that the appointment of Sharon is completely
in line with "our desire" for peace.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is considered an influential figure in Israeli politics as
he enjoys wide support among hardliners in the Jewish country.
He has been opposing to making compromise in the negotiations with
the Palestinians. (Isreal-Sharon-Foreign Minister)
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
condemned the killing of an Israeli woman Friday by a Palestinian
man, saying it underlines Israeli demands that the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) should uproot terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks after an Israeli woman was stabbed
to death by a Palestinian man in the West Bank. Israeli Radio said
the identity of the 20-year-old victim has not been released, but
Israeli army radio reported earlier that she was an Israeli
soldier.
</P>
<P>
Jewish settler leaders urged the Israeli army to enter the
Palestinian village where the assailant lives to punish his
family, saying that Israel should not give up lands to the
Palestinians and expect them to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at about 11 a.m. (0900 gmt) when the
woman was waiting for a bus at a road crossing near the Jewish
settlement of Tomer, about 10 kilometers north of the
Palestinian-ruled town of Jericho. (Israel-Killing) 
</P>
