<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Be Bridge Between China, Britain: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Friday expressed
his hope that Hong Kong will become a bridge between China and
Britain when the two countries embark on a new era of relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner in honor of visiting British Prime
Minister Tony Blair Friday evening, Tung said that a relationship
of friend between China and Britain is vital to Hong Kong, a city
in which the two countries can meet in commerce, in culture and in
friendship to create lasting bonds and benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Hong Kong is now proudly a part of China but Hong
Kong and Britain will always have a special relationship." The
relationship is one of history, of culture and of partnership in
almost every field of social, academic, artistic, sporting and
business endeavor.
</P>
<P>
He noted that many thousands from Britain still make their
homes in Hong Kong, and contribute to the society and the
government; many thousands from Hong Kong still live in Britain,
study there and delight in all that Britain offers to the world.
</P>
<P>
Blair Friday also highlighted the striking links between
Britain and Hong Kong in a luncheon speech. He said that Hong Kong
is the 12th largest export market of Britain, and 40 percent of
Britain's exports to China go through Hong Kong. Britain absorbs
80 percent of Hong Kong's investment in Europe. "Hong Kong, once
the barrier, has become the bridge between Britain and China,"
said Blair.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister flew in here from Shanghai Friday
morning on the last leg of his five-day official visit to
China. He is scheduled to leave here Saturday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
