<HEADLINE> Greek, Spanish Teams Abandon Attempt on Nepal Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Two teams from Greece and
Spain had given up attempt to climb the 8,167-meter Mt.
Dhaulagiri I, the seventh highest peak in the world, the Nepali
Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation released Friday.
</P>
<P>
A five-member Dhaulagiri '98 Hellenic Alpine Club of Athens
Exp., led by Ioannis Katrivanos, quit on Thursday at an altitude
of 7,750 meters, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Its member Charalampos Tsoupras has been missing since October
2 at Camp III (7,550m.) due to snow storm. Pavlos Tsiantos, the
mountain guide from Greece, was injured in the snow storm.
</P>
<P>
Tsiantos was airlifted from the base camp to Kathmandu Friday
morning by a helicopter, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a nine-member Tolosako Espedizio Dhaulagiri 98 of
Spain abandoned on Tuesday at an altitude of 7,700 meters due to
strong wind and heavy snowfall.
</P>
<P>
The Juan Jose Elola Lekuona's team reached the base camp
(4,400m) on September 19.
</P>
<P>
Both teams tried to conquer the peak from the northeast ridge,
the ministry added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
