<HEADLINE> Liaoning Accelerates Small State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 620 small and
medium-sized of state-owned industrial firms in northeast China
Liaoning Province, or 46 percent of the total, have completed
reforms involving equity ownership.
</P>
<P>
Related enterprises had adopted measures suited to their
respective conditions.
</P>
<P>
Some 246 enterprises, or 39.1 percent of the total, have
introduced the joint stock system. An additional 137 enterprises
sold to profitable firms, with 161 ventures either involved in
mergers or joint ventures with overseas partners.
</P>
<P>
A large number of enterprises engaged in structural reforms
have stressed either maintaining or increasing the value of state
assets and creating job opportunities for laid-off workers, said
Wang Binhua, director of the Provincial Economic And Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Accelerating reform of small and medium-sized firms supported
growth of the province's gross domestic product and provided job
opportunities to idle workers due to underproduction, according to
Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
