<HEADLINE> Russia Insists on Peaceful Resolution of Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia is insisting on resolving
the Kosovo conflict only by peaceful means, Russian President
Boris Yeltsin confirmed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, who had just
returned from Athens after talks with the Greek military leaders,
Yeltsin said, "We wish to get a political settlement through
talks, without the use of force, and, I believe, we will achieve
this."
</P>
<P>
The president said that a NATO strike at Kosovo "should not be
allowed".
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Sergeyev said that the Greek government
fully shared Russia's views that the Kosovo crisis must be settled
by political means. Athens confirmed that any NATO military
operation in Kosovo "will be conducted without Greece's
participation", the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev also warned, "If NATO decided to strike at
Yugoslavia, that country will fight to the end.
</P>
<P>
"If strikes are dealt, they will not be a unilateral punishment
of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic "is ready to sit down at
the negotiating table, but so far there is nobody at the other end
of the table", Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev also reported to Yeltsin on the present state and
prospects of arms deals with Greece, which the two sides regard as
positive, and the two countries' cooperation in the modernization
and production of military hardware. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
