<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Back Diplomatic Efforts in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- NATO and Russia agreed Friday
to support diplomatic efforts to seek a solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a special meeting at ambassadorial
level of the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council (PJC).
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors from NATO and Russia exchanged information and
views on the situation in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the meeting said both NATO and Russia
had reiterated their deep concern about the serious humanitarian
crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also stressed the need to see immediate, full and
irreversible compliance with the United Nations Security Council
resolutions, which have demanded Yugoslavia withdraw its forces
from Kosovo and end its military action against the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The special PJC meeting was held in the wake of Thursday's
three-hour Contact Group meeting in London, where the foreign
ministers of the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy
and Russia met to prescribe a list of six demands for Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke was sent back to Belgrade
after the London meeting for his fourth mediation attempt within
the week.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright did not say whether
Holbrooke's trip was the last of its kind after she met with NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana in Brussels on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Albright warned that the western military alliance could
act within the "next few days" if Belgrade failed again to comply
with the U.N. resolutions or the demands of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Russia, however, has been threatening to veto any U.N.
resolution which authorizes NATO military intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov also went to Belgrade
before going to London for the Contact Group meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
