<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Holds Talks with Pak Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General's
Special Envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi held talks here
Friday with Pakistani officials headed by Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, it was stressed that generous humanitarian
assistance was urgently required not only for the reconstruction
of Afghanistan but also to facilitate the return of Afghan
refugees, according to a press release issued by the Foreign
Office Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, assistance was needed for crop substitution in order
to eliminate the cultivation of poppy, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, who arrived here Thursday night from Tehran together
with Assistant Secretary General of the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) Ibrahim Bakr, said during the talks that his
immediate concern was the reduction of tension between Iran and
Afghanistan so that progress can be made on other issues that
would lead to the promotion of peace.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he would visit Afghanistan at an appropriate
time and prior to that he hoped to hold consultations with the
Taliban authorities in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
He had received an invitation from the leader of Taliban, Mulla
Omar, to visit the country and accepted it with pleasure, said the
special envoy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he expressed his appreciation of the efforts being
made by Pakistan for facilitating his mission as well as for the
restoration of durable peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, which lasted almost two hours, the foreign
secretary of Pakistan stressed that the situation in Afghanistan
had reached a critical stage.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the participation of the OIC in the mission for
peace restoration in Afghanistan and assured the delegation of
Pakistan's fullest support and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi's current visit to the region is in the context of
implementing the Points of Common Understanding that were reached
during the Six Plus Two foreign minister's meeting in New York on
September 21.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the Six Plus Two group, which
comprises Afghanistan's immediate neighbors plus the U.S. and
Russia, evolved Points of Common Understanding which include the
cessation of hostilities in Afghanistan and a number of confidence
building measures to promote the restoration of durable peace.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary underscored the need for the U.N. to play
the role it owes to itself in terms of the U.N. Charter with a
view to promoting peace and security by averting the risk of a
conflict between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the importance for timely action to discourage
any precipitous action that could ignite a conflict there.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi was briefed about the measures taken by Pakistan to
reduce the tension generated by the concentration of Iranian
troops along the Afghan border.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Shamshad informed Brahimi that since the Six
Plus Two meeting Pakistan has maintained intensive contacts with
the Taliban leadership to implement the Points of Common
Understanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sensitive Index on BSE Gains 20.52 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, 0ctober 9 ( Xinhua) -- The sensitive index on the
Bombay Stock Exchange ( BSE) market Friday closed at 2,916.66
points as against Thursday's close of 2,896.14, netting a gain of
20.52 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also edged up by 5.54 points to 1,301.05
from previous close of 1,295.51.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the U.S. dollar index were quoted moderately up
at 304.24 and 119.58 points compared with previous close of 302.95
and 119.04 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Equities failed to maintain higher levels even as the sensitive
index somewhat stabilized with a moderate rise reflecting gains in
a few index scrips on the stock market Friday mainly on short
covering and fresh support from foreign funds and domestic
institutions. 
