<HEADLINE> Turkish-Syrian Crisis To Be Solved Diplomatically: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iranian Foreign Minister
Kemal Kharrazi said here Friday that the most important thing is
to find a peaceful solution to defuse the escalating tensions
between neighboring Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who arrived in Ankara Friday morning following his
visit to Damascus, is exerting efforts to find ways to ease
the mounting Turkish-Syrian tensions.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, Kharrazi said that the peaceful
solution to the crisis between Ankara and Damascus is "the
joint wish of all the Muslim countries".
</P>
<P>
In his part, Cem first extended thanks to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatemi and Kharrazi for their friendly approach to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that "they know our concerns, they are trying to
contribute to a solution which will satisfy our concerns. We
will continue to negotiate with Kharrazi."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi added that "We held talks both in Damascus and
in Ankara to solve this problem. We are fully informed about
the issue. this is a very important and difficult job. We
hope to find a solution if everything goes well, but it is
early to say something."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused of Syria of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting a 14-year-old
separatist war for an independent state in southeastern Turkey
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
It has been massing troops since last month along its border
with Syria and threatened to uproot the alleged military camps of
the PKK inside Syria by force if Syria does not stop supporting
the PKK in 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Syria has criticized Turkey for forming a military alliance
with Israel, which it says will endanger the interests of the
Arab world and undermine its bargaining positions in the
negotiations with the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
