<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Spanish Commissioner Upbeat About Trade With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish Trade Commissioner
in Hong Kong, Ernesto Tejedor, said he feels confident of and
optimistic about his country's trade with China's mainland and the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Tejedor also said he
believed that Hong Kong's economy could soon recover from the
regional economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
"As a giant market with great potential, China is our target
market in the future development. There are some 50 million
consumers with very high buying capability," the commissioner
said.
</P>
<P>
Tejedor was confident of China's economic future. "There is no
problem so far as its economy continues to develop rapidly with
foreign investments coming in," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's economy, more closely linked with other parts of
the world, could recover its vitality soon, although it is
suffering from the results of the regional financial crises,
Tejedor said. "As soon as the results of the bubbles economy is
overcome, Hong Kong's economy could soon recover, in maybe one or
two years," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
"It's something temporary and it will not affect our investment
and business interest in the Hong Kong market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Spanish trade with Hong Kong during January-June 1998 was
valued at 1.1 billion U.S. dollars. That indicates Spain should
still see increases in trade in some segments this year even
amidst the Asian economic downturn, Tejedor said.
</P>
<P>
Spain's overall exports to Hong Kong in the first half of 1998
reached 478 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Spanish companies and exhibitors had an enthusiastic and strong
presence at two recent international exhibitions in Hong Kong --
the Asia Pacific Leather Fair and the international beauty
industry trade fair Cosmoprof Asia, in a show of confidence on the
part of Spanish manufacturers in the important Asian market.
</P>
<P>
Some of Spain's beauty product categories are enjoying rapid
growth in Hong Kong and China's mainland, and Spanish leather
goods are available in quality retailers in both Hong Kong and
China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
After Japan, Hong Kong is Spain's second largest trade market
and is just ahead of China's mainland. But Spanish exports to
China's mainland and Hong Kong this year are expected to surpass
those to Japan for the first time in history. "That is really a
good news," Tejedor said.
</P>
<P>
Spanish exports to Hong Kong this year are expected to reach
650 million to 700 million U.S. dollars, an increase of 10 to 15
percent over last year. "This is very good results compared with
the dramatic decrease of our exports to the surrounding
Southeastern Asian countries like Indonesia (80 percent) and
Thailand (50 percent)," he continued.
</P>
<P>
And Spain's exports to China's mainland this year are estimated
to be 600 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Spain has so far done footwear promotions in China's mainland
only through Hong Kong. About 50 percent of Spanish exports to
Hong Kong are eventually re-exported to China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
But with a second Spanish trade representative office
established in Shanghai in November this year, Spain will begin
next year its leather products promotion in China's mainland for
the first time, he said. Spanish companies will also participate
in Fairs in Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to do more business there," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
