<HEADLINE> Philippine Presidential Palace Dismisses Coup Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace Friday dismissed speculations that a coup against the
Joseph Estrada administration may be staged when the president
pays a four-day state visit to Singapore starting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Both National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre and Executive
Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in separate interviews that the coup
is not likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said that Vice President Gloria
Macapagal-Arroyo will be the acting president during his trip to
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
However, Senator Miriam Santiago hinted that a coup may be
staged when Estrada leaves the country, citing that the vice
president may end up running the country for the rest of the
six-year presidential term.
</P>
<P>
She hinted that some power-hungry opponents of President
Estrada are desperate to cut Estrada's term short and his trip to
Singapore could be the perfect time to stage a coup against him.
</P>
<P>
"That would not happen because firstly, the vice president is a
very democratic person. She knows the limits of her power and she
has also very good relations with the president," Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
"I would say such forces are not existing because the Estrada
administration has a very strong support from the people," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also branded as "mere speculation" Santiago's warning of
a coup.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there's any reasonable chance that something as
untoward as a coup d'etat would take place," Zamora said, adding
that Macapagal-Arroyo will only be the caretaker of the government
for a few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
