<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Race Still Affects Job Chances in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Four years after the
introduction of a democratic South Africa, race still plays an
important part in getting a job in the country, Statistics South
Africa (SSA) has found.
</P>
<P>
White South Africans who did not have matric had a 32 percent
chance of finding a job, while their black counterparts had only
an eight percent chance, according to the national institution's
unemployment report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the report found the gap was narrower among blacks
and whites who had matric, with whites having a 56 percent chance
of finding work compared with blacks' 49 percent chance, local
newspaper Business Day reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed that race was still a key issue in
determining whether those who did not have matric become employed
or not, SSA head Mark Orkin said. But he added that blacks who
had matric were rapidly being absorbed into managerial jobs.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive report, released ahead of the presidential
job summit at the end of this month, highlighted a number of
trends, including a shift in employment from the formal to the
informal sector and high rates of unemployment among the youth,
women and blacks.
</P>
<P>
Over the last four years, informal sector jobs grew by 600,000
as the overall economy shed 500,000 formal sector jobs, the
report showed.
</P>
<P>
The informal sector was larger than estimated, with 1.8
million people being employed, while the formal sector hired 7.5
million people.
</P>
<P>
Overall unemployment rose from 20 percent in 1994 to 22.9
percent last year, and joblessness rates were highest among the
youth at 35 percent, the report said. Nonetheless, South
Africa's labor absorption rate continued to decline.
</P>
<P>
In the report, SSA used, for the first time, the International
Labor Organization's definition of unemployed, a narrower
definition than previously used in the country.
</P>
<P>
The previous broader definition reveals that unemployment rose
from 31.5 percent in 1994 to 37.6 percent last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Hit 141.1 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange
reserves soared to 141.1 billion U.S. dollars by the end of
September, up 1.2 billion dollars since the end of last year,
according to the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today show that the central bank's
implementation of financial policies combined with effective
measures and improvements in banking services have accelerated
growth of the money supply. Increases have also been recorded in
loans and deposits and the stability of the yuan has been
maintained.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding volume of broad money (M2) stood at 9.98
trillion yuan at the end of September, up 16 percent of the 1997
period. The volume of narrow narrow money (M1) rose 13.2 percent
to 3.65 trillion yuan, with outstanding amount of money in
circulation (M0) ending the period at slightly over 1.05 trillion
yuan, up 11.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Loans outstanding for all financial institutions grew by 17.1
percent to over 8.2645 trillion yuan. The accumulated loan volume
for the first nine months of the year grew by 761.2 billion yuan,
a substantial 125.5 billion yuan rise on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding deposits for all financial institutions ended the
period at close to 9.188 trillion yuan, up 17.3 percent; of which,
enterprise deposits grew by 14.8 percent to 3.086 trillion yuan,
individual deposits grew by 17.1 percent to 5.158 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits for the first nine months grew by 578.9 billion
yuan, some 43 billion yuan more than in the same period of
1997. Commercial banks continued to maintain a sufficient payment
ability.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate for yuan remained stable at 8.278 to the US
dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
