<HEADLINE> Uganda Declares 3 Major Cities No Fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army has declared
Kampala, Jinjia and Entebbe, the three largest cities in the
country, a no fly zone which took effect this week for security
reasons, The Monitor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The army commander Major-General Jeje Odongo confirmed the
development Thursday evening and was quoted as saying that this
move is intended to secure national security.
</P>
<P>
"There is growing violation of our air space. This is a
normal action taken for security reasons that bear in mind
threats from Sudan," the army commander noted.
</P>
<P>
"We have communicated and the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA)
of Uganda must by now have alerted international airlines. Any
aeroplane that comes within the no fly zone must consider itself
a possible target," Odongo warned.
</P>
<P>
The report said the move taken by the army may affect all
commercial, charter and scheduled flights.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor also quoted deputy director of the Military
Intelligence Major Noble Mayombo as saying that the air force has
stepped up air defense in light of hostilities from Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Sudanese planes had bombed areas in
northern Uganda. 
</P>
