<HEADLINE> Seoul, Pyongyang Disagree Over Dead Cattle Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea on Friday denied an
allegation by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
that the oxen donated to the DPRK died as they were fed with harmful
materials in South Korea before shipment in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Calling the allegation groundless, South Korea proposed a joint
investigation with the DPRK into the case.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK said Thursday that 71 of the 500 oxen donated by South
Korean Hyundai Group founder Chung Joo-young died and autopsies
showed they were fed with indigestible materials, such as vinyl
and rope, before their shipment.
</P>
<P>
In its investigation report sent to the South Korean Red Cross
Society, Pyongyang said "pieces of vinyl and ropes were found in
the stomachs of all of the dead oxen."
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang also said most of the survivors were in bad condition
and deaths were being reported almost every day.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK urged the South Korean government to punish those
responsible and ensure no recurrence of similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
Chung Joo-young brought the oxen with him in June this year
when he went to the DPRK to tap tourism potentials of the
Mountain Kumgang area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Air Ordered to Suspend 138 Domestic Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government Friday
ordered Korean Air to suspend 138 flights on 10 domestic routes
for six months from October 25 due to recent spate of accidents.
</P>
<P>
Korean Air passenger planes have been involved in seven
accidents, with 70 passengers injured, in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The flag carrier has been operating 933 flights a week on 25
domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
"These accidents in such a short time caused widespread
uneasiness over air travel and dealt a blow to the national
economy," said the Ministry of Construction and Transportation
Friday after its month-long probe into the accidents.
</P>
<P>
The forced suspension is expected to amount to a loss in
revenue of 40 billion won (29.39 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Among the flights to be suspended, 40 are between Seoul and
Pusan, 25 between Seoul and Cheju, 12 between Seoul and Taegu, and
13 between Seoul and Ulsan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will order the suspension of two
international flights a week between Seoul and Tokyo from next
year after a Korean Air plane skidded off the runway at Seoul
Kimpo International Airport narrowly averting a crash.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said it had decided to launch a task force to
conduct safety checks on Korean Air over the six-month suspension
to prevent further accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
