<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Beneficiary of Asian Market Crisis: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Losses of other Asian markets
will mean India's gains, as India is poised to be the big
beneficiary of the currency meltdown in the region, said a report
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Equity sell-off and currency falls across Asia have left India
with the third-highest capitalized market behind Hong Kong and
Taiwan, said the report by the All India Association of
Industries.
</P>
<P>
There are various reasons for the shift in the focus of foreign
institutional investors. India is now emerging as one of the
favored destinations for fund managers "at the expense of Hong
Kong, Malaysia and Singapore", the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these developments India has moved up from being
the sixth highest capitalized country in Asia, excluding Japan, to
the third position with market capitalization of 90 billion U.S.
dollars as on August 11, 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from being the third largest market, India also has
significant amount of companies with over a billion U.S. dollars
in market capitalization, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
