<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Become Regional Innovation, Technology Center, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong could become, within
 a few years, the center of innovation and technology of the
region, Professor Chang-lin Tien, former chancellor of the
University of California at Berkeley, said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong could also be a world-class design and fashion
center, a regional center for multi-media based information and
entertainment services, a world center for the development of
health food and pharmaceuticals based on Chinese medicine, a
leading supplier of value added components and products, a
regional supply center for professional and technological talents
and services, and the marketplace for technology transfer between
China and the rest of the world, Tien said.
</P>
<P>
These were some of the key points in a vision outlined here
Friday by Tien when he presented the first report of Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa's Commission on Innovation and Technology
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Tien was appointed chairman of the commission in March this
year when the commission was set up.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong SAR government must invest at least five billion
HK dollars (641 million U.S. dollars) in fostering innovation and
technology and setting up an Applied Science and Technology
Institute, Tien said at a press conference on the report Friday.
</P>
<P>
To invest less would be a waste of money, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said in the report: "Hong Kong faces a number of major
challenges. There is a strong competition from neighboring
countries for Hong Kong's regional roles in trade, finance,
transportation and communications."
</P>
<P>
"With respect to manufacturing, Hong Kong must strive to
retain, support and further develop high value-added activities.
Hong Kong is also facing stiff competition from other low-cost
economies in the low-end product category," he added.
</P>
<P>
"A fundamental challenge is how Hong Kong should position
itself in the knowledge-based global economy of the 21st Century,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Tien said, "The vision of making Hong Kong a center of
innovation and technology is a timely response to these
challenges."
</P>
<P>
He said that innovation and technology increased the
competitiveness of firms by introducing more efficient ways to
perform existing activities or creating greater buyer value. They
may be applicable to every aspect of the value adding change.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that Hong Kong's science and technology base
should be strengthened. "The government should adapt its
education and manpower policies to address employment issues
brought about by innovation and technological change," he added.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the vision would be a long-term process and a major
challenge to Hong Kong, he said. While industry must make its own
choices and investments, the government should play the role of a
promoter, facilitator and supporter.
</P>
<P>
He suggested in his report that the SAR government should,
among others, build up a human capital, meeting the needs of a
fast changing, knowledge-based economy; enhance technological
collaboration with China's mainland; foster university-business
partnership and low information, financing and regulatory
barriers.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of a talent pool and the free flow of
talents is as important as the free flow of capital," he said.
</P>
<P>
And the Hong Kong SAR could not realize the vision by lonely
efforts. "Hong Kong should collaborate with south China cities
like Shenzhen as well as the Pearl River Delta," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tien said that the first report was presented to the chief
executive so that feedback could be collected from the community.
The commission is set to complete its work by June 1999 when it
presents its final report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
