<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges Investors to Make Use of Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has urged investors to
make full use of locally produced items to enhance the country's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the Shoprite retail shop of South Africa in
Mazabuka, southwest of Lusaka, Minister of Local Government and
Housing Bennie Mwiinga said the investors should contract local
farmers and manufacturers to stimulate economic growth, according
to Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the influx of South African products like
bananas, carrots and tomatoes which are available locally but
imported into Zambia by Shoprite.
</P>
<P>
If investors are not satisfied with the quality of the local
products, then there is need for the investors and the local
farmers and manufacturers to come up with strategies on how to
produce items to the required specifications, he said.
</P>
<P>
Products such as milk, chickens, vegetables and beef which are
in abundance in Mazabuka should not be imported as they could be
supplied by local farmers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shoprite General Manager Mauitz Alberts said Shoprite is
dealing with about 103 local suppliers in Zambia and that it is
buying local supplies worth of 6.5 billion Kwacha (about 3.3
million U.S. Dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
So far the shopping chain has employed about 1,200 people in
its countrywide network of shops, according to Alberts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
