<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec Premier Hints at Fall Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Lucien Bouchard, premier of
Canada's French-speaking province of Quebec, gave his strongest
hint that an election might be called this fall, a national
newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm tempted to give a go to an election in the fall. And I will
have to make a decision about it very soon," Bouchard was quoted as
saying by Canada's leading newspaper the Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we have to stop the conjecture. ... And I think that
people are entitled to know whether or not there will be an election
this fall," he said.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Bouchard left open the possibility of a spring
election. But he said on Thursday that it is normal for a
government to call an election after four years in power.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard's Parti Quebecois (PQ) party was elected on September
12, 1994 for a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Several election dates had been suggested. Quebecers could go to
poll as early as November 16, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Recent polls indicated that PQ's support in the province was
catching up with the opposition Liberal Party, which got a big boost
when Jean Charest became its leader early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
