<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Approves New Drug for Migraine Sufferers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Health Canada has approved a new drug
that promises quick relief for migraine sufferers, the Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The drug, zolmitriptan, is the latest in a family of molecules
known as triptans that researchers believe block signals from the pain
generator in the stem of the brain.
</P>
<P>
"It's not easy to treat migraines, so we're pleased to have a new
soldier join the battle," Yves Meloche, a neurologist who heads the
Montreal Migraine Clinic, was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said triptans mark an important evolution in the treatment of
migraines, and approval of the new drug should send a message that
help is available to sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The prescription drug, sold under the brand name Zomig, is a
product of Zeneca Pharmaceuticals. It costs 12.95 Canadian dollars
(8.4 U.S. dollars) a pill.
</P>
<P>
It is thought that 3.2 million Canadians suffer migraines. These
headaches affect three times as many women as men, principally because
of hormonal triggers during menstruation and menopause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
