<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Heading to Mild Recession Next Year: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada is heading into a "mild
recession" in 1999, according to a new economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
The gloomy forecast, from J.P Morgan Securities Canada Inc., is
believed to be the first to predict that Canada will experience not
just a slowdown in growth, but a shrinkage of gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The predicted slide into recession will drive Canada's jobless
rate up to almost 10 percent and inflation rate down to 0.5
percent, said Morgan Canada's economist Ted Carmichael.
</P>
<P>
At last count, Canada's unemployment rate was 8.3 percent and
the inflation rate 0.8 percent, the Globe and Mail newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Canada will try to revive the slumping economy with
interest rate cuts that will amount to 1.75 percentage points over
the next year, Carmichael said.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate cuts would not be able to prevent the country's
GDP from contracting in both the second and third quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Canada's economic growth would resume in the fourth quarter of
1999, but for the year as a whole, total GDP growth would fall 0.1
percent from its 1988 level, according to the forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
