<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Complains about Aid Conditions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official has
complained that the economy of his country has been badly hit by
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Valenting Kayope told the press here
Thursday when returning from bilateral negotiations with the
European Union (EU) that his country is in the worse economic
position due to its failure to meet some of the donors'
conditions, The Post newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that political dialog should not be one of the
conditions attached to aid.
</P>
<P>
Zambia presented a statement during the negotiations
underlining the fact that conditionalities are not necessary in
securing financial support from the donors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kayope, who led a six-member delegation to Brussels, Belgium,
for preliminary talks, said the African, Caribbean and Pacific
(ACP) and EU negotiations will be based on private sector
investment, trade and financial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations, which started on September 30, will review
contractual agreements between the ACP and EU and are expected to
last 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
