<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Govt to Safeguard Non-Muslim, Women's Rights: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday assured non-Muslims and women that his government
would fully safeguard their rights.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made the assurance after the National Assembly passed
the 15th Constitutional Amendment Bill which makes the Holy Quran
and the Sunnah of the Holy Prophet the supreme law of the country,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
"It is my foremost duty to protect their rights as Islam fully
guarantees the rights of non-Muslims and women," said the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that the Constitutional Amendment
would break the status quo in the country which "is main hurdle in
the dispensation of justice to the poor and oppressed people."
</P>
<P>
"There is law of jungle prevailing in the country and it could
not be changed under the existing system," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
He said the enforcement of Islamic Shariah would guarantee
dispensation of justice to the oppressed people at their
footsteps.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister further said that "we want to make Pakistan
a cradle of peace and social justice where the voice of the
down-trodden is fully and properly heard."
</P>
<P>
"I want that the problems of the poor are resolved and the
cancer of injustice, terrorism, violence and corruption that has
afflicted our society is removed," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the 15th Constitutional Amendment Bill, the federal
government shall be under an obligation to take steps to prescribe
what is right and to forbid what is wrong, to eradicate corruption
at all levels and provide substantial socio-economic justice, in
accordance with the principles of Islam, as laid down in the Holy
Quran and Sunnah.
</P>
<P>
Nothing contained in this Article, the Bill says, shall affect
the personal law, religious freedom, traditions or customs of
non-Muslims and their status as citizens.
</P>
<P>
The provisions of this Article shall have effect
notwithstanding anything contained in the Constitution, any law or
judgment of any court, according to the Bill.
</P>
<P>
The Bill was passed with the required two-thirds majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
