<HEADLINE> British Digital Technology Showcased in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- With the arrival of British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, an exhibition highlighting the
state-of-the-art digital technology products opened in Hong Kong
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bringing together one of the largest displays of digital
technology ever shown in the city, "High Definition -- British
designs for digital future" is a major new exhibition at a busy
shopping center, the Pacific Place, and features more than 80
futuristic products.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits, set against a sophisticated multimedia backdrop,
include design prototypes for the world's first GSM video phone,
an imaging system for personal computers called intellicam that
enables the "clicking" of an icon without touching the screen, an
interactive music retailing device called vibrant chair, and a
biological feedback system that can help manage human stress
levels.
</P>
<P>
As a symbol of the exhibition, a virtual "digital girl" named
Kate Young will introduce to visitors the products, categorized in
living, learning, leisure, and creativity. Organizers hope the
exhibition will be attractive to both children and adults.
</P>
<P>
The five-day event was specially organized for Hong Kong by the
British Council and the British Consulate General. 
</P>
