<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Employers Reminded not to Cut Wages for FDHs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Labor Department
Friday reminded local employers of foreign domestic helpers (FDHs)
to pay their FDHs wages in line with the employment contract,
which should be no less than the minimum allowable wage stipulated
by the government.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said the department is concerned about media
reports that some FDHs are being recruited and paid at wages less
than the minimum allowable wage of 3,860 HK dollars (494.87 U.S.
dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
"Employers should pay their FDHs no less than the wage amounts
specified in their standard employment contracts," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Employment Ordinance, underpayment of wages is a
prosecutable offense in Hong Kong. An employer who underpays his
employee is liable to prosecution and, upon conviction, to a
maximum fine of 200,000 HK dollars (25,641 U.S. dollars) and to
imprisonment for one year.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman advised any FDH who is being underpaid to
approach the Labor Relations Service of the Labor Department for
advice and assistance. "All complaints alleging underpayment of
wages will be investigated by the department," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also reminded employment agencies that they
should not conduct job placements involving FDHs at wages lower
than the minimum allowable wage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
