<HEADLINE> Lagos Civil Servants Begin Strike over Minimum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Civil servants in the Lagos
State, Nigeria, began an indefinite strike Friday to press for
the payment of 5,200 Naira (about 60 U.S. Dollars) monthly
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday, the Council of Industrial
Unions (COIU) in Lagos State directed about 60,000 workers to
stay at home from Friday "until otherwise directed by the
council" due to the continued refusal to respond to the demand
for the payment of minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
The COIU issued a three-day ultimatum Monday to the state
government to pay the new wage or face an industrial action
throughout the Lagos State, This Day newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Lagos State Administrator Col. Mohammed Buba Marwa
said the state government was not in a position to pay the new
salaries as approved last month by the federal government for its
civil servants.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the state's monthly revenue was 930 million
Naira (about 10.8 million U.S. Dollars) while the new salaries
will cost the government 850 million Naira (about 10 million
Dollars) monthly.
</P>
<P>
The face-off took a new turn Wednesday when the state
government sacked COIU Chairman Ayodele Akele on the pretext of
his anti-government activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the industrial unrest taking place in the Rivers
State entered the seventh day Friday over the same issue and
civil servants in other states may follow suit in the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Ruling Council, Nigeria's ruling body, is
reportedly scheduled to hold a meeting next week in Nigerian
capital Abuja to tackle the growing industrial unrest over higher
wages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
