<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Killing of Israeli Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu condemned the killing of an Israeli woman Friday by
a Palestinian man, saying it underlines Israeli demands that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) should uproot terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks after an Israeli woman was stabbed
to death by a Palestinian man in the West Bank. Israeli Radio said
the identity of the 20-year-old victim has not been released, but
Israeli army radio reported earlier that she was an Israeli
soldier.
</P>
<P>
Jewish settler leaders urged the Israeli army to enter the
Palestinian village where the assailant lives to punish his
family, saying that Israel should not give up lands to the
Palestinians and expect them to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at about 11 a.m. (0900 gmt) when
the woman was waiting for a bus at a road crossing near
the Jewish settlement of Tomer, about 10 kilometers north of
the Palestinian-ruled town of Jericho.
</P>
<P>
The assailant, who came from a nearby Palestinian village,
was captured after Israeli security forces opened fire and hit
in his legs, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Palestinian man was being interrogated while
he was treated in an Israeli hospital, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several people were injured in the West Bank
town of Hebron as hundreds of Palestinians clashed with Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The clashes erupted before a funeral for a Palestinian who
was killed by Israeli soldiers in a clash Thursday. The
Israeli newspaper The Jerusalem Post said the 21-year-old man
was a Jordanian who was apparently visiting his relatives in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The stabbing Friday cast a shadow for the coming Washington
summit next week between Netanyahu, PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat
and U.S. President Bill Clinton, during which an agreement is
expected to be reached on the Israeli second withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been mounting in the West Bank since Israel sealed
off the areas and the Gaza Strip last month following the killing
of two members of the Islamic militant group Hamas by Israeli
troops.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has repeated its threat to attack Israelis for
retaliation, including committing suicide bombings and kidnaping
hitchhiking Israeli soldiers. 
</P>
