<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Confident of Full Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) told visiting
British Prime Minister Tony Blair Friday afternoon that he was
confident of a full recovery of Hong Kong's economy and held a
positive long-term view of the future of the city.
</P>
<P>
During a one-hour meeting, the chief executive exchanged views
with Blair on the latest development of the Asian financial
turmoil, SAR government sources said.
</P>
<P>
Tung also briefed the prime minister on the political and
economic challenges people in Hong Kong had experienced since
Hong Kong's return to China last year.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's economy, the chief executive said that there was
"no quick fix" while fully appreciating the short term economic
difficulties that Hong Kong is facing.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR government has been introducing immediate and timely
measures in response to latest economic changes over the past few
months," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The measures include fiscal measures in February, a market
stimulation package in June and measures for the financial market
in August. Altogether they amount to 53 billion HK dollars (6.8
billion U.S. dollars) in terms of tax cuts and government
expenditure, according to Tung.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the measures will not only provide some
degree of relief, but will also lay a solid foundation for the
recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to creating the best possible environment for
our economic development, and we look forward to continuing and
increasing British participation in our economic development,"
Tung added.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive also assured Blair of Hong Kong's
commitment to the linked exchange rate and the maintenance of a
free and open market.
</P>
<P>
The SAR has no plan for foreign exchange control, Tung told
Blair.
</P>
<P>
"I am encouraged by the initiative taken by the prime minister
in advocating a new global order for the international financial
market," Tung said. "There is a need for concerted efforts among
nations, in particular the G7 members, in order to take the matter
further."
</P>
<P>
Tung also reiterated Hong Kong's commitment to a "strong and
robust framework" that was essential for the development of
democracy in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Hong Kong from Shanghai earlier Friday on the
last leg of his five-day China visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
