<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists to Hike Though World's Largest Canyon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expedition team
composed of some 20 scientists and climbers will hike through the
Yarlung Zangbo River Canyon, thought to be the world's longest and
deepest, during a 50-day exploration.
</P>
<P>
"A great many of the world's wonders are expected to be
discovered during the expedition," Gao Dengyi, head of the team and
executive vice-chairman of the China Association of Scientific
Expedition, said here today at a setting-out ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Located on the southeastern region of the Tibet-Qinghai
Plateau, known as "the roof of the world," the Yarlung Zangbo
River Canyon is about 496 kilometers long with an average depth of
more than 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Before Chinese scientists made careful studies of the canyon in
1994 and identified it as the world's largest, the Grand Canyon in
the southwestern United States and the Cerro Colca Canyon in Peru
had been considered the longest and deepest canyons in the world,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some experts from the State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping
will use the Global Positioning System and other modern scientific
methods to ascertain the exact length and depth of the canyon, and
will share the data with the whole world, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
"That won't alter the fact that the canyon is the largest in
the world," Gao pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The team plans to take Chaqu, a small village on the top of the
horseshoe canyon, as the expedition's base. From Chaqu, the team
will then explore the upper and lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Gao said that no one has ever before attempted to hike through
one particular 15-km section in the central part of the canyon,
and their effort will be the first.
</P>
<P>
The team members also plan to find a 60-m high and 150-m wide
waterfall which has been seen by the locals.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to find it. If it does exist, it must be one of
the largest falls in the world," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists on this trek are from various fields such as
atmospheric science, botany, zoology, geography and environmental
science. Rebecca Lee Lok-si, an explorer from Hong Kong and vice
chairman of the China Association of Scientific Expeditions, will
join the exploration.
</P>
<P>
The first exploration of the canyon, which is expected to find
many new plant and animal species, will provide precious materials
for the study of the Tibet-Qinghai Plateau, said Yang Yichou, a
geographer with the team.
</P>
<P>
The team sent 20 people on a walk through the canyon in April
this year, he added, and this was good preparation for the
large-scale expedition now.
</P>
<P>
The expedition team also includes television and newspaper
reporters, and a documentary film of the journey will be produced
and released worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police to Investigate Soeharto's Brother-in-law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian police are
investigating the issuance of 3 billion U.S. dollars worth of fake
promissory notes, a case which allegedly involves former president
Soeharto's brother-in-law Ibnu Hartomo.
</P>
<P>
"The Attorney General's Office, which has found the case to be
criminal in nature, has submitted it to the police," police
spokesman brig. Gen. Togar Manatar Sianipar told Antara News
Agency Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ibnu, who was deputy chief of the National Resilience Board in
1986, allegedly issued fake promissory notes for a housing project
for members of the military.
</P>
<P>
Sianipar said this is a violation of Article 264 of the
Criminal Code on faking valuable notes, which carries a penalty of
a maximum of eight years in jail.
</P>
<P>
The case was uncovered in 1991 when two Americans sued the
Indonesian government because they could not encash the notes.
</P>
<P>
"Ibnu has not yet been investigated as we are still questioning
witnesses. A special team is ready to leave for the United
States," Sianipar said.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib has said foreign parties were
pressing the government to pay for the promissory notes.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto resigned on May 21 amid a deepening economic crisis,
protests and an explosion of rioting in Jakarta in which almost
1,200 died.
</P>
<P>
Public pressure to bring Soeharto to account for alleged
corruption and cronyism has mounted since the former president
resigned.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie has set up an official probe into his
predecessor's wealth because of the allegations that Soeharto and
his family amassed a fortune during his 32-year rule and stashed
it abroad. 
</P>
