<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Sales Drop 70 Percent in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Coca-cola sales dropped 70
percent in Zambia following last month's sharp price increase
from 500 Kwacha to 900 Kwacha a bottle.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted John Graham, Country Sales and
Marketing Consultant of the Coca-Cola company, as saying here
Thursday that the company has incurred a 70 percent loss in
business after the price increase.
</P>
<P>
The company, Zambia Bottlers, last month increased prices of
its pruducts, coca-cola, fanta and spirte by 80 percent because
of what it said high duty imposed on raw materials.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the Zambian government promised to reduce
the excise duty on Coca-Cola from 25 percent to five percent, but
it failed to meet its promise. In September, the company
suspended its production, but later said it would remain
operational in Zambia despite the controversial excise duty.
</P>
<P>
The company said that it is concerned about the government
inability to honor its promise but expressed its confident that
the government will settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Some government officials have branded the company as a
"black-mailer" which has for a long time been evading taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
