<HEADLINE> Bank of Thailand Not to Intervene on Baht Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Finance Minister
Pichet Panvichartkul said the Bank of Thailand did not act to
influence the movement of the baht on the foreign exchange market
recently, the Thai News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to stress that no one has done anything to the
baht. The move (strengthening baht) has been made by market
forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
The baht has strengthened sharply over the last six or seven
days and hit a high of 38.44 to the U.S. dollar Thursday from
between 40 and 41 baht against the dollar at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kitt Patpongpibul, deputy governor of the Bank of
Thailand, said the firmer baht signals well for the government to
keep interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
He said the firmer baht will benefit the government policy of
easing interest rates. He attributed the renewed baht strength to
improved investor confidence which resulted in increased capital
inflows.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Bank of Thailand will keep a close watch
on the baht movement to ensure it would not be too volatile or
move to fast for corporations and industries to adjust themselves.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
