<HEADLINE> Thai National Airways Cancels Aircraft Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai National flag carrier, Thai
Airways International (THAI), announced Friday that it has
canceled orders for one Airbus Industrie A330-300 and two Boeing
777-300s as part of its cost-reducing and fleet adjustments.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation came after Thai Transport and Communications
Minister Suthep Thueksuban ordered the order withdrawal on
September 30 to help save Thailand's expenses, Thai News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
THAI said it would inform Airbus Industrie and Boeing
Commercial Airplane of its decision to cancel the order for the
aircraft which had not been on production lines.
</P>
<P>
The national airline had placed a deposit of 148 million
dollars for the aircraft and was required to pay another 216
million dollars to complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
The three aircraft were part of the 21 new planes that THAI had
planned to buy during 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
THAI said it would instead lease new aircraft as part of its
fleet modernization. Earlier reports said THAI was making another
negotiation with Airbus Industrie to change a purchase contract
for five Airbus 300-600s into an 11-year lease deal.
</P>
<P>
The five aircraft were already completed but THAI had yet to
find a budget to pay for their delivery. THAI has already paid 9
million dollars in fine plus interest for having the delivery
delayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
