<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Hire More Teachers to Curb Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
plans to employ another 4,000 primary and secondary school
teachers this year in a bid to curb the rising illiteracy,
Tanzanian education minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing teachers and students of the Tabora Teachers
Training College recently, Minister of Education and Culture
Professor Juma Kapuya said that to arrest the situation, the
ministry has worked out strategies to employ more teachers in
both government and private schools by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The east African country's literacy rate has dropped from 87
percent to 75 percent due to the shortage of teachers, said
Kapuya.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports Friday, the ministry is carrying
out a census on the number of teachers who are on the government
pay-roll because it seems that many teachers who have resigned or
died are still listed.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the census is completed, the government will employ
teachers in primary and secondary schools at village, district
and regional levels, said Kapuya.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank report shows that crippled by heavy external
debt, Tanzania is spending less and less on education.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,600 teachers so far have been employed this year,
the minister said, adding that the goal for this year is 6,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
