<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenyan Economic Recession to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's economy will remain
depressed into the next year, the Central Bank of Kenya said in
</P>
<P>
The lasting recession is "mainly because of the problems in
coffee and sugar production and the adverse effects of the recent
bomb blast in Nairobi," said the economic review.
</P>
<P>
The looming global recession is also expected to further erode
prospects for Kenya's economic recovery by reducing consumers
demand and depressing the prices of the country's exports, it
added.
</P>
<P>
"The depressed performance is evident in almost all sectors,"
the bank said, citing such key reasons as current fiscal
imbalance, lack of working capital, reduced investments caused by
high cost of domestic funds and low investor confidence, poor
state of infrastructure and insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's real gross domestic product (GDP) grew by about 1.5
percent in the year ending in June 1998 compared with 2.3 percent
in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance is also reflected in low trading at the
Nairobi Stock Exchange, whose share index stood at 2,853.1,
declining by 17.7 percent in the year to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is estimated to have grown by only 0.6 percent in
the year to June 1998 compared with 4.4 percent and 1.2 percent
in 1996 and 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in agricultural growth stems from the lz"=
June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The value of coffee ex in the firstive months of 1998
declined by 24.7 percent to seven billion Shillings (117 million
U.S. Dollars) compared with 9.3 billions Shillings (155 million
Dollars) over the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports of horticultural products declined by 11.6 percent in
the year to June 1998 compared with 4.5 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Tea production, however, continued to recover particularly in
the first half of 1998 with its output increasing by 29.4 percent
in the year to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from tea export also rose by 89.0 percent to 15.5
billion Shillings (2.58 billion Dollars) in the first five months
of 1998, thanks to the favorable international price and the
El-Nino rains that boosted output in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's manufacturing output growth rate went down to 1.4
percent in the year to June 1998 from 3.7 and 1.9 percent in 1996
and 1997 respectively, resulting from the sector's inability to
compete with cheaper imports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade, restaurant and hotel estimated to have
fallen to 3.1 percent in the year to June 1998 from 8.0 percent
and 3.9 percent in 1996 and 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Transport, storage and communication declined to 1.3 percent
in the year to June 1998 from 4.0 and 1.8 percent in 1996 and
1997. The poor performance in the sector was mainly caused by
the poor infrastructure, particularly roads.
</P>
<P>
Finance and insurance in the country is also estimated to have
declined to 4.6 percent in the year to June 1998 from 7.1 percent
and 5.2 percent in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank vowed to take appropriate measures
including reducing the public debt to avert any further decline
in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government's domestic debt rose to 151.8 billion
Shillings (2.53 billion U.S. Dollars) at the end of August, from
150.4 billion Shillings in July, the CBK said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy ran into trouble last year after the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a key loan on the
grounds of official corruption and poor "governance" in the
country, a decision which sent interest rates soaring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
