<HEADLINE> UN Refugee Agency Slams Report by US Rights Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) on Friday refuted a report by the U.S.-based
Human Rights Watch which criticized the UNHCR's efforts to help
Myanmar refugees stranded in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable that Human Rights Watch did not check with
the UNHCR before releasing their report this week, since it did
not take into account recent developments," the UNHCR office in
Bangkok said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The group said the UNHCR had been "unnecessarily weak in its
efforts to challenge the Thai policies that undermine refugee
protection."
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR statement said the report had ignored the Thai
government's invitation to the agency to expand its role in
helping the Myanmar refugees on the Thai-Myanmar border and open
new offices in three provinces there.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR had announced earlier that it would open three
offices in three Thai border provinces to help resettle the
refugees at the Thai government's invitation.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that the UNHCR's expanded role at the border, in
close cooperation with the Thai government, will contribute to
enhancing the protection of the refugee population," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 100,000 Myanmar refugees are stranded on
Thailand's western border with Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Thai government officials had said earlier that Thailand, as a
host to refugees and displaced persons, recognized the need for
international solidarity and burden-sharing as the solution to
refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also called on the international community to provide
financial support that would enable the UNHCR and related
organizations to cope with the refugee problem more effectively
and sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Myanmar refugees, there are some 38,000
Cambodians in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, 8,177 displaced persons have been
voluntarily repatriated under the UNHCR assistance, and some
37,000 have returned spontaneously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
