<HEADLINE> Cambodian Tripartite Talks Again Make No Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The third round tripartite
negotiations of Cambodia's three major political parties ended in
a stalemate again Friday, but they all agreed to hold a summit
meeting under the auspices of King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Sar Kheng, chief representative of the Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) and co-minister of interior affairs, told reporters that
Friday's talks yielded no concrete results because the two
opposition parties -- the Funcinpec and the Sam Raincy Party (SRP)
-- stuck to their positions held since July's election, which made
things complicated.
</P>
<P>
"But the participants agreed to hold a three-party summit
meeting under the auspices of the King in order to break the
current political deadlock," Sar Kheng said.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, who met with the French
ambassador to Cambodia Friday, said he remained optimistic about
breaking the current political deadlock which he described as a
"temporary atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
The CPP, which is the winner of the National Assembly election
on July 26 but does not gain the two-thirds majority needed to
form the government on its own, is eager to see a new government
installed so the government can regain international legitimacy it
lost after last year's faction fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Funcinpec and the SRP have claimed that the CPP's electoral
victory was achieved through fraud and intimidation. The two
parties insisted their allegations be thoroughly investigated
before the National Assembly can hold first official meeting.
</P>
<P>
The working groups of the Funcinpec and SRP still demand a
change in the seat calculation formula and a general amnesty for
all opposition politicians and supporters facing court action for
their roles in anti-government demonstrations staged after the
election. 
</P>
