<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Falls Further in Kenya  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Month-on-month overall
inflation in Kenya continues to fall to 4.0 percent in September
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) said.
</P>
<P>
The decline came after the sustained slowdown in the expansion
of money supply, stability in the Shilling exchange rate and
recently better supplies of basic foods, according to the October
issue of the CBK Monthly Economic Review available Friday.
</P>
<P>
The underlying month-on-month inflation fell to 8.4 percent in
September from 9.8 percent in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Three months annualized underlying inflation remained low at
1.6 percent last month. The average annual underlying inflation
remained at 9.3 percent in September, nearly the same level as in
August.
</P>
<P>
The overall inflation also declined substantially in
September, mainly thanks to the improvements in the supply of
basic foods, particularly to the lower income group.
</P>
<P>
Three months annualized overall inflation fell to negative
16.7 percent in September from negative 13.6 percent in August
and average annual overall inflation declined to 8.1 percent from
8.4 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The CBK said in order to keep the underlying month-on-month
inflation at below five percent by June 1999, it will maintain
tight fiscal policies to curb the expansion in the broad money
supply in the year to June 1999 at below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling on money supply takes into account the expansion
in domestic credit that results from the recent reduction in cash
ratio requirement.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the decline in the international prices of
essential imports, particularly fuels, had also contributed to
the fall in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Kenya experienced double digit inflation during the early
1990s, with the three month's annualized rate
reaching a three digit figure of 101.1 percent in
June 1993 but by late 1994 inflation subsided to single digit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
