<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Parliament Passes 15th Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of
Pakistan Friday passed the 15th Constitutional Amendment Bill
which makes the Holy Quran and the Sunnah of the Holy Prophet the
supreme law of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bill provides that the federal government shall be under an
obligation to take steps to prescribe what is right and to forbid
what is wrong, to eradicate corruption at all levels and provide
substantial socio-economic justice, in accordance with the
principles of Islam, as laid down in the Holy Quran and Sunnah.
</P>
<P>
Nothing contained in this Article, the Bill says, shall affect
the personal law, religious freedom, traditions or customs of
non-Muslims and their status as citizens.
</P>
<P>
The provisions of this Article shall have effect
notwithstanding anything contained in the Constitution, any law or
judgment of any court, according to the Bill.
</P>
<P>
The Bill was passed with the required two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Parliamentary Affairs Muhammad Yasin Watto, who
moved the Bill, said the Bill will bring socio-economic justice to
Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
