<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merged Zambian Opposition Urged Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian opposition parties have
been urged to concentrate on finalising their merger before
holding inter-party talks with the ruling Movement for Muti-Party
Democracy (MMD).
</P>
<P>
Dante Saunders, Secretary General of the Zambia Democratic
Party, said in an interview here Thursday that the opposition
parties needed to merge into one strong group to be able to
bargain with the MMD in the proposed inter-party talks, Times of
Zambia reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Saunders criticised the MMD's motive to resume the talks,
saying the ruling party had realised that the opposiiton was in
the process of coming together and deliberately brought up the
idea of resuming the failed talks to disturb the merger.
</P>
<P>
The MMD and three of the country's 18 opposition parties, the
United National Independence Party (UNIP) led by former president
Kenneth Kaunda, the Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC) and the
National Party (NP), Wednesday set October 21 as the date for a
preparatory meeting to resume the inter-party talks which flopped
last year after Kaunda was arrested for an alleged involvement in
the foiled military coup in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
The talks are designed to solve in the country's political
process some outstanding issues such as re-registration of voters
and amendament of the existing constitution proposed by the
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Saunders also invited other interested politicians to join the
planned merger if they wanted to defeat the MMD during the next
presidential and parliamentary elections in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition parties in the past weeks had been moving to
merge so that they could speak with "one united voice" to finally
dislodge the MMD from governing in the general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
