<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister on Kosovo Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan in a meeting with Yugoslavian ambassador to China Slobodan
Unkovic today expressed deep concern over developments in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
China holds that the Kosovo issue is the internal affair of
Yugoslavia, and the threat to use of force by some countries has
aroused intensive worries, he said.
</P>
<P>
It should be noticed, Tang indicated, that massive military
conflicts have terminated in the region, and the situation at
large has tended to ease. And the relevant sides are striving to
seek a settlement of the issue through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Given the above facts, Tang said that any military action
targeting Yugoslavia will violate the United Nations Charter
and other universally acknowledged international regulations, and
will do nothing but make the situation more complicated, or
even give rise to serious outcome.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is China's consistent stand to oppose
resolutely the use of force or threat to the use of force in
international relations.
</P>
<P>
The international community, China included, is making enormous
efforts for seeking a political settlement of the Kosovo crisis,
with the relevant sides undertaking diplomatic consultations.
</P>
<P>
He voiced his hope that all sides will take still more active
measures to implement the relevant UN resolutions, pay more
attention to the human factors, and cooperate in a constructive
way with the international community, "all of which will
undoubtedly contribute to the final settlement of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government hopes that the Kosovo crisis will be
resolved peacefully as early as possible on the premise of
respecting the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia, and ensuring the legitimate rights and interests of
various ethnic groups in the region, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Unkovic said the Yugoslavian government highly
appreciates China's principled stand toward settling the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is opposed to military interference from other
countries, and will continue to adopt measures to create
conditions for the settlement of the issue by political means, the
ambassador added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0188 </DOCNO>
