<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Hydrological Systems Reduce Flood Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts calculate that
losses of more than 40 billion yuan (about 4.8 billion
U.S. dollars) during this summer's deluge along the Yangtze River
could have been greater if not for information provided by the
country's hydrological systems.
</P>
<P>
Ji Xuewu, director of the Hydrological Bureau under the Yangtze
River Water Control Commission, said that the bureau's
hydrological systems along the Yangtze provided timely and
accurate information for decision-making during this summer's
flood fighting.
</P>
<P>
This information enabled flood-control departments to drop
plans to control floods, and thereby reduced the number of flood
victims by over nine million people and the flood-affected area by
more than 16,000 sq km, according to Ji.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the six flood-peak periods along the
Yangtze alone, hydrologic information helped reduced losses by
more than six billion yuan (about 725 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ji said that his bureau has 866 hydrometric stations, 481
water-level stations and over 4,200 precipitation monotoring
stations along the Yangtze River, forming a large information
network.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the central and provincial governments have
earmarked some 200 million yuan (24 million U.S. dollars) annually
to the development of hydrological systems along the Yangtze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0195 </DOCNO>
