<HEADLINE> Sino-French Organizations Expand Regional Cooperation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nord-Pas de Calais, the third largest export region in France,
Calais forged friendly ties with Tianjin, the largest port city in
north China, some 14 years ago. The region's trade volume with
China is expanded to hit four billion Francs (741 million US
dollars) over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The RDA has helped small French companies obtain numerous
orders from China, including a contract with a Tianjin cement
plant for heavy machinery valued at 7.4 million US dollars. The
agency has also helped a number of French companies establish
joint ventures throughout China.
</P>
<P>
China exported goods valued at 556 million US dollars worth of
goods to Nord-Pas de Calais over the past few years, with the
region exported 71 million US dollars worth of wheat, wool,
chemicals and steel products worth 71 million US dollars to China.
</P>
<P>
Lille Mayor Pierre Mauroy met with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin during his September visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Eugene Johnson, the RDA official in charge of the China market,
said that small- and medium-sized enterprises account for 30
percent of Sino-French joint ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects the importance for regional development agencies
to provide assistance to related enterprises," according to
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
Morel noted that local regions in the two countries continue to
enjoy fruitful cooperation. The Shanghai office for the Rhone Alps
Region has helped over 80 French companies to find
cooperative partners in China.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed Tianjin municipal official pointed to the highly
satisfactory cooperation between the city and the Nord-Pas de
Calais, saying that China needs advanced technology and equipment
developed in the French region, and noting that the two sides are
considering expanding cooperation to the environmental protection
sector. 
</P>
