<HEADLINE> Turkey Determined to Solve Problem with Syria: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem has said that Turkey this time is determined to solve
the protracted problem of Syria's support to Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Daily News, which was
published Friday, Cem said that Turkey has made up its mind
to take some effective measures to ensure peace and tranquility
of its borders.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion there is a determination. This is the best
definition for the present situation," Cem said.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, Turkish government and military leaders
issued stern warnings against the Syrian administration over the
alleged Damascus' backing of Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Worker's
Party (PKK) militants.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament Wednesday, Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz said that Turkey has to make preparations for a
war against Syria if there is really a need for that.
</P>
<P>
Cem noted that the fact Syria provides financial and
military support to the PKK is well-known to all and Turkey,
as a sovereign country, realized that the situation had gone
beyond all the limits of patience.
</P>
<P>
"How many lives would we have saved and how many billions
of U.S. dollars would we have spared if we had shown this
determination 10 or 12 years ago?" Cem stressed.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Syria should halt its support for
separatist terrorism and put a full stop to this problem.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish foreign minister said that Turkey's
determination is by no means aimed at the Syrian people who
are regarded by Turks as their own brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
"We have no problem with the Syrian people. Our problem
is with the Syrian administration. They should get into action
and relations should get into a better mode." he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria have long been at odds over the PKK problem
which the Syrian government has repeatedly denied. Disputes over
water resources and border issues are also factors preventing
normalization of their ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
