<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building Industry Becomes Pillar of China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The construction industry has
witnessed steady growth over the past two decades and has emerged
as the pillar industry of the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
The sector accounts for more than 60 percent of China's total
fixed asset investments, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector's incremental output accounts for 6.7
percent of the nation's gross domestic product, holding fourth
place following the industrial, agricultural and commercial
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The industry has completed housing with total a floor space of
4.4 billion sq.m. over the past 20 years, as well as a large
number of infrastructure projects which have greatly improved the
living standards of Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita floor space for urban residents jumped to 8.8
sq.m. in 1997, up dramatically from only 3.6 sq.m. in 1978, with
the figure for rural residents rising from 8.1 sq.m. to 22 sq m.
</P>
<P>
The expanded industrial scale has substantially increased the
number of employees in the sector, with recent statistics showing
that the 44,000 construction firms at the fourth level and above
employ more than 21 million people.
</P>
<P>
The industries equipment and technical level has improved
greatly and China currently ranks at forefront worldwide in terms
of constructing large buildings and highrise complexes.
</P>
<P>
China's construction industry has opened ever wider to the
outside world. The seven construction contracts firms in the
industry consummated in 1978 involved totalling of only two
million US dollars of funds. However, the 8,442 contracts signed
in 1997 were valued at 11.4 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
