<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Plot to Kill Lesotho's King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa turned down
allegations that there was a plot to assassinate Lesotho's King
Letsie III, The Citizen newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force (SANDF) spokeswoman
Laverne Machine said Thursday that the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) task force was still protecting the
palace in Lesotho capital Maseru as a priority.
</P>
<P>
She also denied reports of plans by the SANDF to storm the
palace Thursday to remove protesters who have been camped out
there since August 4.
</P>
<P>
The allegation was an opposition ploy to advance its cause and
to demand for a government of national unity, said the report
quoting a senior South African government source.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the alleged assassination plan, Lesotho's
opposition alliance spokeswoman Mamello Morrison said: "The
information was given to us by a private secretary to the king
because they had received very disturbing information that they
wanted to find out what the implications were."
</P>
<P>
Morrison said the call from the private secretary was coupled
with information received by protesters that the SADC task force
was planning to storm and bomb the palace Thursday in an effort
to get rid of the protesters.
</P>
<P>
She said that opposition leaders had spoken to South Africa's
political party and church leaders to ensure something is done to
stop it.
</P>
<P>
"We seem to have successfully done that because it was happily
denied by the people in Pretoria," she said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if she knew who was planning the assassination, the
opposition spokeswoman said she did not.
</P>
<P>
However, she directly implicated Lesotho Foreign Minister Tom
Thabane in the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the negative attitude he has displayed during the
talks so far, I can't put plans like this from him," she said.
"He was the only one opposed to plans (for a transitional
structure) so far."
</P>
<P>
The king's brother Seeiso Seeiso said: "The whole thing came
about yesterday (Wednesday). I don't know where it came from, but
there was a request that His Majesty be taken to a safe area.
</P>
<P>
"I can't say for certain who the source of the rumor is and I
don't know how true or valid it is," he said. "But there are
some people who are uncomfortable with his position. It seems to
be a repeat of the events of 1990 when King Moshoeshoe was taken
out of the country."
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's Environment and Women Affairs Minister Mamoshebi
Kabi was applauded Thursday when she questioned the need to have
a monarchy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Kabi told the Lesotho National Assembly that the time had come
to seek a mandate from the electorate to decide the future of the
monarchy.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen quoted a source close to SADC-brokered talks as
saying that people were raising these issues to create a
diversion from the real issues at hand, such as the establishment
of the transitional structure for new elections.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho ruling party and its opposition rivals agreed last
week to hold fresh general election in 15 to 18 months, but they
failed to agree on who would run the country until then.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's talks, the parties agreed to consider a SADC
proposal on the establishment of a transitional structure to
prepare for the elections. The rival parties will meet again
next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
