<HEADLINE> Guangdong Border Police Tighten Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The border police force in
southern China's Guangdong Province has set up a frontier command
post as part of an effort to ensure the smooth return of Macao
to China.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the border police force organized an exercise to
sharpen the frontier guards' ability to handle potential
situations in Hengqin, an islet close to Macao.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Jieyuan, commander of the frontier troops in
Guangdong, more than 500 soldiers have been sent to Zhuhai to
reinforce public security work in that city, adjacent to Macao.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the number of frontier guards stationed on Hengqin
islet has increased to some 250 to crack down on illegal border
crossings into Macao.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that Guangdong and Macao police have established close
ties and increased cooperation, and the two sides meet once every
month to brief each other on major events and discuss ways to
fight illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
From January to September this year, border police in Zhuhai
seized 583 people trying to sneak into Macao, 79 of whom were
"snakeheads," or organizers of illegal border-crossing
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
