the current bloody conflicts between the Yugoslav security forces
and the ethnic Albanian armed groups which have lasted for months.
</P>
<P>
The attendance of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has
not yet been confirmed, but Yugoslav diplomats said that the
possibility of his coming has not been ruled out completely.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and his Greek counterpart
Costas Simitis, who will draw the most attention, are expected
to hold a face-to-face meeting on the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the graveness of the situation in Kosovo, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana has informed Turkish Foreign
Ministry that he will not be able to come to the Balkan summit.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief was expected to undertake a mediation effort
between Greece and Turkey at the summit. 
