<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Study: Exercise Reduces Stroke Risk by 46 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 8 (Xinhua) -- People who did the
equivalent of an hour's brisk walking every day had a 46 percent
lower risk of stroke than people who did not exercise, according
to a study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on a survey of 11,000 Harvard graduates between
1962 to 1990, also found that those who did the equivalent of a brisk
half-hour walking most days had a 24 percent lower risk of stroke than
those who did not.
</P>
<P>
"Walking, stair-climbing and participating in moderately intense
activities such as dancing, bicycling and gardening were shown to
reduce the risk of stroke," Dr. I-min Lee of the Harvard School of
Public Health said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"We found that doubling the effort showed an even greater reduction
in stroke risk," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Lee and his team reported their findings in the latest issue of
the American Heart Association's journal Stroke and recommends people
to get at least half an hour of such moderate exercise each day.
</P>
<P>
"We know that physical activity can reduce blood pressure and help
slow the development of clogged arteries, keep weight down, reduce a
person's cholesterol levels and help reduce the clotting of blood,"
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Stroke is the third-biggest cause of death in the United States,
after heart disease and cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
