<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in Tokyo
Friday for a second straight day with the key Nikkei index hitting a
new 12-year closing low as the Japanese yen's sharp rise against the
U.S. dollar deflated the shares of top-flight exporters to new lows
for the year.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 146.09 points, or 1.12
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 12,879.97.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei's close was its lowest since the 12,888.94 marked
January 23, 1986.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 19.00 points or 1.90 percent to 982.50.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 600 million
shares from Thursday's 527.56 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
It was another day of heavy profit-taking for dollar-based foreign
investors, who jettisoned huge amounts of export-led shares to cash in
on the firmer yen, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,337 issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 664 to 455, with 154 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar drifted lower
against the yen to fall more than 2 yen off the day's high.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 117.18-22 yen at 5 p.m. (local time), down
from 118.15-20 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and from 119.10-20 yen late
Thursday in New York.  
</P>
</TEXT>
