<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Opposition to End Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korean opposition Grand National
Party (GNP) Friday announced it will return to the National Assembly,
or parliament, to fight against what it called the ruling camp's
politically-motivated scheme.
</P>
<P>
"Our party has decided to return to the National Assembly. We will
now move our struggle to the National Assembly to stage a stronger and
more effective protest," GNP Chairman Lee Hoi-chang said at an
unexpected press conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
The GNP has been boycotting the 100-day regular session of the
parliament due to open on September 10 to protest at an ongoing
prosecution authorities' corruption probe, which the opposition
described as the ruling camp's politically-motivated scheme to weaken
and break up the GNP by use of the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
In August, the prosecution authorities found that the GNP had used
leading figures of the Office of National Tax Administration to
collect huge sums of money in donations to support its presidential
candidate Lee Hoi-chang during last year's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors are investigating into the behaviors of some 200
people, including legislators and high ranking public servants, as
well as executives of banking institutions and corporations.
</P>
<P>
The latest confrontation between the GNP and the ruling camp of
the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and the United
Liberal Democrats (ULD) focused on members of Lee Hoi-chang's
presidential campaign team who allegedly tried to turn the
presidential campaign into Lee Hoi-chang's favour last year by
asking the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to stage
a shootout at the truce village of Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
The GNP vowed to mobilize all legal means to clear various
allegations and demanded an investigation to determine whether
President Kim Dae-jung himself contacted the DPRK just before the
presidential election last year.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined to have an independent counsel appointed for an
unbiased investigation on politicians and on presidential campaign
fund, said GNP leader Lee Hoi-chang at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The opposition's decision came just one day after the ruling camp
announced Thursday that it will open a unilateral parliamentary session
from next Tuesday if the GNP continues to boycott the assembly when
many urgent issues have to be resolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
