<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Supports HKSAR's Efforts to Ride Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Friday expressed his support to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government for its resolve to lift
Hong Kong out of the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I pay tribute to the Administration here and its leader for
the manner in which they have sought to guide the SAR through a
crisis not in any one economy's ability to control," Blair said at
a luncheon shortly after he flew in from Shanghai on the last leg
of his five-day official visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Saying people naturally look for immediate answers for urgent
problems, the British prime minister warned: "This is not a time
for re-writing the rules that made Hong Kong one of the envies of
the world."
</P>
<P>
"It is a time for holding firm to basic principles, being
truthful about what can and cannot be done," Blair said in a
luncheon address. He praised the SAR's efforts to maintain Hong
Kong's dollar peg and China's determination not to devalue the RMB
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current crisis, he noted, Hong Kong continues to
stick to its long-held vision of an open world economy, with
liberalized trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome Tung Chee Hwa's renewed commitment in his policy
address to open markets, without exchange controls, and to Hong
Kong's standing as an international center for trade and finance,"
said Blair. "You are absolutely right to stick to openness."
</P>
<P>
He praised the SAR government for its policy decision not to
cut, but to increase the education budget in times of economic
difficulties, a decision which is "right for the long term."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister enumerated many advantages Hong Kong has to
help itself through the crisis, including a transparent system of
regulation, prudent macroeconomics policies, open and liberal
environment for trade and investment, a well-capitalized banking
system, an open and disciplined administration, a level playing
field, and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Blair said Hong Kong's political transition has been a success
despite the buffeting in its economy by the global financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"On Hong Kong, those who predicted failure have been proven
comprehensively wrong. The handover has been a success," he told
the luncheon, jointly organized by the British Chamber of Commerce
in Hong Kong and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
He noted: "China has honored her commitment to Hong Kong's
autonomy. Hong Kong, once the barrier, has become the bridge
between Britain and China."
</P>
<P>
More than one year after he last came to Hong Kong for the July
1 handover ceremony, the British prime minister also told the
audience what else has impressed him here in Hong Kong: "The rule
of law is robust. Basic freedom and rights continue to be
respected and exercised. The people of Hong Kong speak out and
demonstrate on issues they care about."
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay in Hong Kong, the British prime
minister is scheduled to meet with SAR officials and visit a
shopping center and a temple before he leaves on Saturday evening.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
