<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Urges Global Efforts to Withstand Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Friday called for all economies in the world to work
together to withstand the financial crisis, which has expanded on
a global scale.
</P>
<P>
"The financial crisis is global and the methods of dealing with
it must also be global," said Blair in a luncheon speech shortly
after he arrived in Hong Kong on the last leg of his five-day
official visit to China.
</P>
<P>
He said it is urgently needed to "tackle successfully both the
immediate consequences of the crisis and its longer-term causes."
</P>
<P>
In the short term, the major economies of the world, mainly G-7
countries, must work closely together for prudent financial
policies and sustainable economic growth, said Blair.
</P>
<P>
He continued:" It is time to look afresh at the international
financial system, to devise new rules and codes of practice to go
with it, which not only measure up to the volume of capital moving
about global financial markets but also its speed."
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister said the fast and enormous flow of
capital around the globe called for a need to review the Bretton
Woods institutions, which have served the world well for 50 years
and still deserve continued support today.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that there is no one simple or quick answer to
the crisis, but added: "It is a challenge to which we must respond
imaginatively and above all rapidly."
</P>
<P>
"We can only move forward on a globally agreed basis, by
including representatives of the wider international community,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair called on the world community to respond to the financial
crisis by working together to maintain openness and overcome
problems, not by retreating into protectionism and isolation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
