<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Urge Continued Stability of Yuan Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 ( Xinhua) -- A report released today by the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences said China should continue to
maintain a stable yuan exchange rate in 1999 and pledge to the
world that the currency will not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
The autumn report of Economic Trend Analysis and Prediction,
compiled by a number of noted Chinese economists, said that a
stable yuan is good for China's economic development and will help
maintain its balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
"Both domestic and international economic conditions since the
start of the Asian financial crisis prove that China's policy of
not depreciating its currency is correct and has profound
significance," the report says.
</P>
<P>
Experts said in the report that the negative impact of the
financial turmoil is still developing and that the economies of
most Asian countries and regions are suffering negative
growth. Hong Kong's economy is also facing grave difficulties,
while at the same time international speculators are flexing their
muscles to attack any detected weak spots.
</P>
<P>
As a result, they noted that a stable yuan exchange rate is
crucial to maintaining stability in the international economic
order and easing the consequences of the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
With respect to China's domestic economy, sharp investment
increase decided by the government will surely push up price
indexes, while a stable yuan will avoid a recurrence of excessive
price hikes and benefit the sustained, rapid and healthy
development of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Rumors about a possible devaluation of the yuan continue, the
report says, but none of them has proved true and the Chinese
currency is still doing very well. At present, China enjoys stable
foreign exchange reserves, a surplus in foreign trade, and
balanced international payments. These factors will enable the
yuan to remain stable in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
