<HEADLINE> Li Ruihuan Meets Jamaican Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), met today with visiting Jamaican Prime
Minister Percival Patterson and said that China hopes to further
consolidate and strengthen Sino-Jamaican ties.
</P>
<P>
The two nations enjoy good relations despite the
geographical separation, and differing historical traditions and
social systems, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese Government and people appreciate the
strong support Jamaica has given China on many leading issues,
especially the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Li reiterated that China has always held that all countries,
big or small, poor or rich and strong or weak, should be equal
politically. China's foreign diplomacy centers on the tradition
of treating others equally, earnestly and reasonably.
</P>
<P>
He said China is fully prepared to further explore the
potential for consolidating and strengthening exchanges and
cooperation with Jamaica in the political, economic and cultural
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Li said Prime Minister Patterson's visit will play an important
role in the further development of China-Jamaica relations.
</P>
<P>
Patterson pointed to Li's successful visit to Jamaica in
1995. He said the Jamaican Government established diplomatic
relations with China in 1972 and fully recognizes that there is
only one China in the world.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that China, one of the world's most
influential nations, has unswervingly supported Jamaica and other
developing countries. He added Jamaica and other countries in the
Caribbean will never forget China's assistance.
</P>
<P>
Paterson reaffirmed that the Jamaican Government is fully
prepared to engage in joint efforts with the Chinese Government
and contribute to the further development of bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
