<HEADLINE> Preparations for '98 China Air Show Near Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Construction of an exhibition
center and related basic facilities for the '98 China
International Air Show in Zhuhai, south China's Guangdong
Province, have been almost completed, an official of the Civil
Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The city, which will host the air show between November 15-22,
has invested one billion yuan (120.48 million U.S. dollars) to
build an 23-km eight-lane highway around the local airport, a
press center covering 8,000 sq.m. and a number of hotels and
conference centers.
</P>
<P>
The parking apron is to be expanded to 500,000 sq.m. to
accommodate 200 aircraft, while a special exhibition area of
50,000 square meters will be ready for the show.
</P>
<P>
Over 860 domestic and foreign companies from 28 countries and
regions will participate in the event, which will feature 120
aircraft and a number of special performances.
</P>
<P>
According to the CAAC official, about one billion people are
expected to view the show on TV, apart from some one million
people present at the show which will be covered by over 2,500
journalists.
</P>
<P>
Space products will also be exhibited in a special hall
covering 3,000 sq.m., with two Long Market rockets on display in a
4,000-sq.m. outdoor exhibition area.
</P>
<P>
The show, the largest of its kind in China, is held every two
years. The first show took place in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Plans to Export Coffee Through Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan coffee exporters are in
negotiations with Coffee Board of Kenya (CBK) over the using of
Kenya's auction facilities to sell their coffee abroad, Kenya
Coffee Auction spokesman Tony Valentine has said.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Friday quoted Valentine as
saying lately that Uganda's Bunsuna Coffee Exporters are seeking
admission to the Nairobi Coffee Exchange to sell Ugandan robusta
coffee.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know how much coffee is involved yet, but the
organization wishes to use our market, and they are quite
impatient to get moving," said Valentine.
</P>
<P>
Uganda produces mainly robusta coffee, and if the proposal is
accepted, it would mean that robusta would be sold together with
Kenya's arabica coffee, a new development for the auction, he
said.
</P>
<P>
CBK spokesman Paul Kivila said that the board will decide in
two weeks whether Uganda's Bunsuna Coffee Exporters will be able
to enter the auction, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Following the complete liberalization of the Ugandan and
Tanzanian coffee industries that did away with central auctions
and official grading, the farmers and exporters in Kenya's two
east African neighbors are having a hard time selling their
coffee.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's coffee export is expected to drop to 2.6 million bags
for this season from last year's 4,237 million bags due to a fall
in production for bad weather, the state-run Uganda Coffee
Development Authority has forecast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
