<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Sino-British Partnership Progressing (1)  by Yu Haisheng and Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair, the
first British head of government to visit China since 1991, today
headed for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), the
last leg of his five-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beijing, Blair and his Chinese counterpart
Zhu Rongji signed a joint statement pledging that China and
Britain will be engaged in setting-up a comprehensive Sino-British
partnership.
</P>
<P>
The statement outlined the framework for the development of a
fresh bilateral relationship oriented to the 21st century, local
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on a state visit to Britain by
Chinese President Jiang Zemin in the second half of next year,
which Zhu and Blair believe will bring steadily growing
Sino-British ties into a "new phase."
</P>
<P>
Zhu and Blair also agreed to establish a Sino-British Forum to
enable people from all walks of life in the two countries to
contribute their ideas to the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The sound development of Sino-British ties has by no means been
a smooth process. During Hong Kong's transition period, the unwise
practices of the British Hong Kong authorities jeopardized
relations and caused serious concern to the people who care about
the future of Hong Kong and the Sino-British relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Sino-British Partnership progressing  (2) by Yu Haisheng and Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese leaders have stated on many occasions that the two
sides should, proceeding from the fundamental interests of people
of both countries, handle their relationship from a long-term
perspective.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair expressed hope that Hong Kong can be a
"bridge" rather than an obstacle between the two countries after
he assumed his post in May of 1997.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to China's important role in the world, and
said that Britain should strive to forge a "wider and
constructive" relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji visited Britain in late March this
year, the first such visit by a head of Chinese government in 13
years. During his visit, Zhu made it clear that there will be no
barriers to the growth of bilateral relations after Hong Kong's
return.
</P>
<P>
Since the return of Hong Kong, Sino-British relations have
experienced warm ties. Five British cabinet members have come to
China since the beginning of this year in a bid to boost political
and economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Clearly, the improvement and development of Sino-British
political relations has created a favorable atmosphere for
expanded economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Britain is now China's second largest trading partner in the
European Union (EU). It also ranks first in the EU in investment
in China this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two countries have facilitated exchanges in
cultural, technological and military areas.
</P>
<P>
China and Britain, as permanent members of the UN Security
Council, enjoy wide-ranging common interests and
responsibilities. Establishing a comprehensive Sino-British
partnership will have a positive impact on world peace and
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
