<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 70 Percent of S.Korean Companies Cut Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 70 percent of South Korean
companies have reduced their staff or planned to do so this year due
to the ongoing financial crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies and
bad loans of financial institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
Under a survey on 424 Seoul-based firms, 69.7 percent have cut down
the number of employees or planned to do so within this year since
South Korea entered the so-called IMF period after it borrowed 58
billion U.S. dollars from the international body last December, said
the Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry Friday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of firms have cut their staff by morer than
10 percent while another 39.4 percent said they have excessive
manpower, showing that the number of layoffs will continue rising this
year.
</P>
<P>
The nation, whose unemployment rate stood at 1.6 million in
September, is seeking to the jobless rate under eight percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
The survey said 65.7 percent have cut their staff due to poor
management performance while 23 percent made layoffs as a part of
restructure.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy, has to restructure its
economy, open market and shut down ailing financial institutions
within this year in accordance with the agreement it signed with the
IMF last December for a rescue loan of 58 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
