<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Prisoners Escape During Massive Prison Relocations: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- During massive relocations of
50,000 prisoners in Jilin, Heilongjiang and Anhui provinces and
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region during this summer's flood
season, not a single inmate escaped, Chinese Minister of Justice
Gao Changli said here today.
</P>
<P>
"This can be regarded as a miracle in the history of
rehabitating and educating the criminals," Gao said at a national
tele-conference commending individuals and organizations of
judicial administrative bodies.
</P>
<P>
Even in the two provinces of Hubei and Jiangxi, where the
floods were most severe, no prisoners ran away, and no
unusual deaths or major epidemics occurred during the
floods, either, he said.
</P>
<P>
In this year's devastating floods, 75 prisons and 21 labor
camps in eight provinces and regions were seriously affected and
many have had to be moved elsewhere. Total economic losses at
prisons amounted to 3 billion yuan (361.4 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Faced with flood disasters rarely seen in history, prison
wardens were on high alert and stuck to their duty to maintain
order and safety at the institutions under their charge," the
minister claimed.
</P>
<P>
No major accidents occurred in the flood-affected areas this
summer, and crimes perpetrated inside prisons were lower than in
the same period last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Awards were presented today to 48 organizations including the
Yueyang Prison in Hunan Province and 121 individuals working in
prisons and other judicial administrative bodies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Busy Planting Autumn Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers, from north to
south, are busying planting autumn and winter crops, and
agricultural technicians say current weather conditions are most
conducive to planting.
</P>
<P>
The planting period will last until December and the main crop
is wheat that will be harvested next summer, said an official of
the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The country will plant more than 30 million hectares of grain
during this period, including 26 million hectares of wheat this
autumn and winter, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Though blessed with high temperatures and sufficient soil
moisture now, the official noted that this season's planting still
faces some unfavorable conditions such as developing drought in
the northern part of the country. The poor quality of wheat seeds
in some places and seriously damaged water conservancy projects
will also pose planting problems.
</P>
<P>
To ensure smooth planting and a good harvest next summer, the
ministry recently published an emergency notice urging local
governments to fight against drought and improve planting
quality.
</P>
<P>
China's agricultural departments also warn of more severe plant
diseases and insect pests this autumn and winter. The notice asks
local governments to spread the use of seed-coating and seeds
mixed with pesticides to ward off insects.
</P>
<P>
Because of the severe floods this year, China's summer grain
harvest fell to 113.1 billion kilograms, 11 percent less than last
year's figure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
