<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Study Finds More Teens Starting to Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of U.S. teenage
smokers have increased by 73 percent in the past eight years, a
study released Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on a survey of more than 78,000 people of all
ages, found that 1.2 million people under the age of 18 became
daily smokers in 1996, the latest year for which figures were
available. The figure was 708,000 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
"More than 3,000 young people under the age of 18 start smoking
every day... some people began smoking daily at 10 or 11 years of
age." said Gary Giovino, chief health expert of U.S. Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, which conducted the survey and
released the findings of the study.
</P>
<P>
Giovino blamed the increase of teenager smokers on the
cigarette companies, whose marketing agents "took on more of a
youth focus in the late 1980s, with the Joe Camel campaign and
some Marlboro promotional campaigns aimed their products at young
people."
</P>
<P>
Tobacco usage in television and movies during the same period
was also a factor, he said.
</P>
<P>
If current trends continue, the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention warned, about 5 million youths will eventually die from
a smoking-related disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Undertakes Program for Post-Flood Field Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Rural Development
Board (BRDB) has undertaken a comprehensive program for post-flood
field service network, said a BRDB press release Friday.
</P>
<P>
The program includes a plan to disburse 5.5 billion taka (about
117 million U.S. dollars) as micro-credit to the flood-affected
clientele.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be disbursed among cooperative farmers, assetless
men and women in the flood-hit areas in the agricultural sector
for increasing income generating activities through its
development project.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a task force was formed to ascertain the damage and
losses as well as needs for providing loans and other facilities
to the cooperators and assetless people, the release stated.
</P>
<P>
The program also includes a plan to disburse one billion taka
(about 21.28 million dollars) as credit support to the agriculture
sector and 3 billion taka (about 63.8 million dollars) to non-farm
activities under poverty alleviation projects of the BRDB.
</P>
<P>
In addition to that, BRDB has planned for an extra allocation
of 1.5 billion taka (about 31.9 million dollars) to meet the
post-flood situation.
</P>
<P>
Within the BRDB areas of cooperation, over 1.7 million
cooperators and assetless men and women in 50 districts have been
affected by the devastating flood, which has caused an enormous
loss to them.
</P>
<P>
The requirement for post-flood rehabilitation under the BRDB
program has been estimated at 10.22 billion taka (about 217.4
million dollars), the release said.
</P>
<P>
The BRDB disbursed 400 million taka (about 8.5 million dollars)
for agricultural rehabilitation and income generating activities
among the flood-affected cooperators during the flood.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the credit facilities, periodical training is
being held to impart skills to the cooperators, assetless men and
women, and from this program, flood-affected people are getting
training allowances as financial help.
</P>
<P>
The recent ten-week-long floods had destroyed crops on 580,000
hectares of land in the country's 52 severely-affected districts,
causing a loss of about 40 billion taka (about 851.1 million
dollars), while farmers lost 3.5 million tons of crops including 2
million tons of rice, according to the Department of Agricultural
Extension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Britain to Meet in 1999 Davis Cup First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Coming off last month's
embarrassing performance, the United States has a tough task
ahead when it meets Britain in the first round of the 1999 Davis
Cup.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will travel to an undetermined site in Britain for a
first-round tie to be held from April 2 to 4, 1999, as the Davis
Cup begins its 100th year. Ironically, the U.S. met the British
Isles in the first Davis Cup in Boston in 1900.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is coming off last month's 4-1 loss to Italy in the
semifinals in Wisconsin, the United States. The Americans were
playing without stars such as Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi and
Michael Chang and now face Britain, which can field a much better
team than the Italians.
</P>
<P>
Playing in the prestigious World Group for the first time
since 1992, Britain has two top-15 players in Tim Henman and Greg
Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Britain tie will be a rematch of the 1978 Davis Cup
final, which the Americans won for one of their record 31 titles.
The U.S. has won the last three meetings, leads the series 10-7,
and has not lost to Britain since 1935.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. wins, it would host either Australia or Zimbabwe
in a quarterfinal tie in Boston.
</P>
<P>
In other first-round ties in the 1999 World Group, Sweden
meets Slovakia, Germany hosts Russia, the Netherlands plays
France, Spain takes on Brazil, Belgium entertains the Czech
Republic, and Italy hosts Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
