<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Global auto major Daimler-Benz is reducing both
its employees and offices in India as part of a restructuring
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz India Ltd (MBIL), a joint venture with the Tatas
in which the German company has an 80 percent stake, has been
incurring heavy losses due to the recession in the automobiles
industry, Business Standard said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
MBIL has started closing offices and trimming employees. At
the same time, it plans to rely increasingly on franchisees and
dealers to push its cars in India. The New Delhi and Chennai
offices have been shut. Industry sources said Mumbai office might
follow suit soon. (India-Benz-Auto Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Ministers and business leaders from the Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) gathered here
Thursday for a two-day meeting on the future of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa meeting is the third of its kind by OECD member
states in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
It represents a major step toward reaching broad consensus on
critical areas of concern to international business and public
policy makers, organizers said. (Canada-OECD-Electronic Commerce)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Financial officials from 182 countries and
regions unanimously endorsed a strategy of cooperation to
strengthen the international financial system in their week-long
debate on how to deal with worsening regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The financial instability, which started 15 months ago in
Southeast Asia and quickly spread to Japan, Russia and across the
Pacific to Latin America, drew the attention of finance ministers
and central bank governors during the joint annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank. (US-IMF-World
Bank) 
