<HEADLINE> Construction of Sri Lanka's Biggest Fishery Harbor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will launch
construction work on the 5.3-million-U.S.-dollars fishery harbor
at Puranawella in the South of the country, according to the
Ministry of Fisheries Friday.
</P>
<P>
The construction work on the project which is being funded by
the Asian Development Bank has been awarded to a Chinese company.
</P>
<P>
The project involves the construction of a 680-meter
breakwater, a 200-meter quay wall and dredging of 9,000 cubic
meters, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Once completed the harbor will have a depth of 3.5 meters,
while its basin will be 10 hectares. It will be able to
accommodate 300 multi day boats at a time .
</P>
<P>
The project which is expected to be completed in 18 months,
will have a fish receiving station, an ice producing factory and
auction halls, said the sources, adding that it will be the
biggest fishery harbor in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
