<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Tumble At This Week's Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Low demand and a higher
Australian dollar have pushed wool prices under a new
500-Australian-cent benchmark for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Auction prices have now fallen 34 percent over the past 12
months and are at their lowest level in five years in Australian
currency terms.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Wool Exchange's (AWEX) eastern market indicator
shed 12 cents to close at 497 Australian cents (305.8 U.S. cents)
a kilogram clean this week.
</P>
<P>
About 18.9 percent of the 83,368 bales on offer were passed in.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters' (ACWE) said in its
weekly market review that there were no visible signs of a
recovery in consumer demand in a climate of continuing global
economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
"The depressing trend in auction prices reflects the reality of
available supply far outstripping a very poor level of demand for
wool," the review said.
</P>
<P>
"In this environment, the sharp appreciation of the Australian
dollar against the U.S. dollar ... was thought to be the reason
for the very large drop in auction prices on Thursday for 22
micron and coarser types, which traditionally comprise the staple
diet of orders for China," the ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
About 76,900 bales are rostered for next week's sales at
Australia's cities of Goulburn, Melbourne and Fremantle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
