NEW DELHI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Global auto major Daimler-Benz
is reducing both its employees and offices in India as part of a
restructuring exercise.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz India Ltd (MBIL), a joint venture with the Tatas
in which the German company has an 80 percent stake, has been
incurring heavy losses due to the recession in the automobiles
industry, Business Standard said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
MBIL has started closing offices and trimming employees. At the
same time, it plans to rely increasingly on franchisees and
dealers to push its cars in India. The New Delhi and Chennai
offices have been shut. Industry sources said Mumbai office might
follow suit soon.
</P>
<P>
"The regional offices will in future be integrated into
prominent dealerships where our managers would serve like
consultants, helping our dealers in this initial phase," MBIL
souses said.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that to pare losses, MBIL had initially
toyed with drastic options for its Indian operations. But that was
dropped in favor of the second option that consisted of continuing
with the production facility in Pune about 1,500 km southwest of
New Delhi while closing down offices.
</P>
<P>
This is a normal business procedure in response to the sluggish
domestic market conditions, MBIL sources said. 
