<HEADLINE> Panama to Set Up Animal Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Panama will set up a reserve
to protect endangered animals in the Panama Canal area, a senior
official of wild life protection said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The animal haven will be located near the area of Howard Air
Base and will extend over 3,500 square meters," said Olga Gaitan,
president of the Animal Friends Association (AFA).
</P>
<P>
The future reserve's land reverted last year to Panamanian
sovereignty from the U.S. government in accordance with the
Torrijos-Carter treaties, which was signed in 1977 by general Omar
Torrijos and former U.S. President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
This zone will provide a veterinary clinic, a mini-jungle for
exotic endangered animals, and a domestic animal shelter, Gaitan
said.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Renewable Resources Institute, in charge of
protecting Panama's wildlife, has listed endangered species of
animals such as the "titi" monkey, the American tiger, the harpy
eagle, parrots, lizards, rabbits and toucans, and many others.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult for these animals to live unprotected, that's
why we must protect them at the haven we will develop near the
Panama Canal," Gaitan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
