before Monday," Agov said.
</P>
<P>
For more than three hours, the MPs of the Foreign Policy
Committee were listening to information presented by the National
Intelligence Service and the President's Foreign Political
Secretary, Vladimir Filipov.
</P>
<P>
The Committee will have a debate on Kosovo before next
Thursday. "I will insist that the Foreign Minister and the
Defence Minister take part in it," Agov said.
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov said that
his country will pursue consistently its policy of remaining
cautious on the Kosovo issue and will act with consideration of
the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"We must be ready to act in any circumstances in the course of
development of the Kosovo problem and to take timely decisions;
our stand should be well-grounded and consistent," Kostov was
quoted as saying by the Bulgarian news media.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. President Bill Clinton said Thursday that
he had authorized U.S. participation in NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia if the latter did not stop its offensive against ethnic
Albanian separatists fighting for independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"NATO must be prepared to act militarily to protect our
interests and to prevent another humanitarian catastrophe in the
Balkans," he said.
</P>
