<HEADLINE> UNHCR to Open Offices in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) plans to open offices in three
Thai provinces along the Thai-Myanmar border in an effort to solve
the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
The offices will be set up in Mae Hong Son, Tak and
Kanchanaburi provinces as soon as possible, the UNHCR said in a
statement available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We expect UNHCR's role at the border, in close cooperation
with the Royal Thai Government, to contribute to enhanced
protection of the refugee population," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR and the Thai government have been criticized for
failing to give adequate protection to more than 100,000 Myanmar
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the criticism, the statement said the report had
not taken recent developments into account, particularly in terms
of the agency's expanded role at the Myanmar border.
</P>
<P>
Based on the principle of solidarity and burden-sharing, the
Thai government reached a common understanding on working
arrangements with UNHCR in May this year to enhance the agency's
role in resolving the problem. The arrangements include witnessing
admission, assisting Thai authorities in registration, assisting
in the relocation of temporary shelters and helping Myanmar
displaced persons with safe return.
</P>
<P>
The arrangements are expected to be implemented this month with
the Thai government and the UNHCR jointly monitoring its
development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the UNHCR will also be granted free access to
refugee shelters.
</P>
<P>
Thai government officials have said that Thailand, as a host to
refugees and displaced persons, recognized the need for
international solidarity and burden-sharing as the solution to the
refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has called on the international community to provide
financial support which should go beyond emergency relief and
should focus on reintegration and monitoring returnees to ensure
the continuity of repatriation and to prevent the recurrence of
outflow.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Myanmar refugees, there are some 38,000
displaced Cambodians in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, 8,177 displaced persons have been
voluntarily repatriated under the UNHCR assistance, and some
37,000 had returned spontaneously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
