<HEADLINE> Italian PM Insists UN Must Authorize Military Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy stepped out of line with its
NATO allies Thursday when Prime Minister Romano Prodi said
military intervention to force a cease-fire in Kosovo must be
authorized by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Rome to parliament, Prodi said Italy would continue
to push for a "peaceful" settlement of the hostilities in the
ethnic Albanian province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"The government intends to maintain its commitment to a
political and peaceful solution to the conflict in Kosovo," Prodi
said, and any military action will "have to be legitimate,"
according to decisions taken by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said Wednesday that member
countries agreed the alliance could intervene in Yugoslavia
without further U.N. Security Council approval.
</P>
<P>
On September 23, the council adopted a resolution demanding
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic halt hostilities in
Kosovo and start negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"We must have a discussion between alliance members," a NATO
spokesperson in Brussels said Thursday, commenting on Prodi's
speech today. "I believe we will find a common position which all
member countries can agree with," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to parliament, Prodi said Italy had recently
stepped up diplomatic attempts to obtain full implementation of the
U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy was committed to "providing full protection to
the affected populations and alleviating the humanitarian tragedy
through every means available."
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo crisis, in which ethnic Albanians have been
fighting for independence since early this year, military
intervention has been suggested by some countries, but the use of
military force in the war-afflicted Kosovo area is still under
debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
