<HEADLINE> Chinese Wins U.S. Professor of the Year Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Jin Hong Gang, professor of
Chinese at Hamilton College in New York state was named by the
Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching the 1998-1999
U.S. Professor of the Year.
</P>
<P>
The award was to recognize her extraordinary dedication to
teaching, commitment to students, and innovative teaching methods,
said the foundation in a news released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Professor of the Year program was created by the
Council for Advancement and Support of Education in 1981 and is
the only national award program that recognizes college professors
for their teaching, and is supported by the higher education
community.
</P>
<P>
Jin won the award of Outstanding Baccalaureate College
Professor. She was among the four winners from 500 nominees by
colleges and universities across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Outstanding Community College Professor was awarded to
Cathleen Kennedy, professor of computer and information science
from College of San Mateo, California; Outstanding Master's
University and College Professor was awarded to Gayle Seymour,
professor of art from University of Central Arkansas; and the
Outstanding Research and Doctoral University Professor award went
to Sujiet Shenoi, professor of computer science from the
University of Tulsa, Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
The Carnegie Foundation awards 5,000 dollars to each of the
winners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
