<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Global Turmoil Calls for Worldwide Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Financial officials from 182
countries and regions unanimously endorsed a strategy of
cooperation to strengthen the international financial system in
their week-long debate on how to deal with worsening regional
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The financial instability, which started 15 months ago in
Southeast Asia and quickly spread to Japan, Russia and across the
Pacific to Latin America, drew the attention of finance ministers
and central bank governors during the joint annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone agrees there is a way out of the crisis. It is an
uphill way, but it is there," said IMF Managing Director Michael
Camdessus following Thursday's closing session.
</P>
<P>
"We have undoubtedly moved a long way forward in identifying
the steps needed to establish a more durable global economic
system and for addressing the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was a ``systemic'' crisis and prompt action was
needed. The financial officials agreed that a global crisis
requires a global response. The architecture of the system needs
to be strengthened to adapt to new challenges.
</P>
<P>
Five key elements of the new architecture -- transparency,
sound financial systems, involvement of the private sector,
orderly liberalization of capital markets, and internationally
accepted standards and codes of good practice -- were endorsed at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting followed a series of meetings held by the Group of
Seven (G-7) most industrialized nations, the Emerging Market
economies, the Group of 24 developing nations, the Group of 22
parties of the industrial countries and emerging markets, as well
as the IMF's Interim Committee and the IMF-World Bank joint
Development Committee.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, industrial countries were called to provide
continuing impetus to sustainable growth at home and abroad, and
especially in Japan, which has been confronted with serious
economic recession. They were also encouraged to take more bolder
and quicker measures to promote economic recovery while repairing
the financial system.
</P>
<P>
Russia has called for a solid program of stabilization and
reform, while developing nations showed determination to maintain
and strengthen their macroeconomic policies and adjustment
programs.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the World Bank were urged to play a stronger role
in dealing with the crisis by increasing their financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Besides the principle statements, there were also some concrete
actions. Japan announced a 30 billion U.S. dollar loan guarantee
program to the crisis-hit Asian nations in a bid to help quickly
overcome the difficulties and revive their economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Brazil will receive a total of 30 billion dollars or
more as the IMF tries to prevent a financial catastrophe in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, President Bill Clinton, who called for a
financial system with a new architecture. He pledged to win the
republican-dominated Congress's approval of an additional 18
billion dollars to increase IMF resources. But Congress to date
still insists on preconditions that may be difficult for other
nations to accept.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which has put together 137 billion dollars in bailout
packages for nations affected by market turmoil so far, expects to
gain an additional 90 billion dollars in resources to prevent a
global financial instability and greater consequences of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
To some criticism that the meeting produced so many promises
and lack of concrete actions, Camdessus said that strategies have
been made and policies have been in place, what is needed most is
implementation of these strategies and policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
