<HEADLINE> Henan Province to Build Waste Water Treatment Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province
plans to build nine waste water treatment plants in cities along
the Huaihe River, one of the country's most polluted rivers, by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the program is to improve urban living conditions
and control pollution in the Huaihe River Valley, according to the
Henan Provincial Construction Department.
</P>
<P>
Projects will be undertaken in Zhengzhou, Pingdingshan, Xuchang,
Luohe, Xiangcheng, Kaifeng, Zhumadian, Shangqiu and Xinyang.
</P>
<P>
The plants, which will be constructed at a cost of 1.7 billion
yuan (204 million US dollars), will raise the average daily
treatment capacity by 1.1 million tons and treat more than 35
percent of the province's urban waste water.
</P>
<P>
Construction of five projects commenced at the end of 1997,
with the remainder set to begin by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
