<HEADLINE> Clinton to Get Involved in Peru-Ecuador Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S.President Bill Clinton will
personally get involved in the Peru-Ecuador peace process to break
the deadlock, Ecuador's President Jamil Mahuad and his Peruvian
counterpart Alberto Fujimori told the press here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During their meetings earlier in the day, the two visiting
presidents agreed to ask the guarantor countries for help to
rescue the process and end the "stagnation" that had prevailed
since last week's talks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. president has invited us to the White House on
Friday. As a member of the group of the Treaty of Rio guarantor
countries, he is expecting negotiations to resume and to be
successful," Fujimori said.
</P>
<P>
The United States is one of the guarantor countries in the
negotiations started in 1995 between Ecuador and Peru. The
guarantor countries also include Argentina, Brazil and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori and Mahuad said the result of talks they held at
Brasilia was a joint communique addressed to the guarantor
countries in which they ask for their collaboration to continue
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador fought wars in 1941, 1981 and 1995, with the
last two over a 49-mile unmarked border in a remote stretch of
mountainous jungle. 
</P>
