<HEADLINE> Italy's Industrial Production up 2% in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy's industrial production will
grow by 2 percent in 1998, the Prometeria Institute, a leading
research institute in the country, predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report ``Analyses of Industrial Sectors,''
Prometeria said industrial production will grow by about 3.5
percent from 1999-2000, after the country undergoes a period of
considerable economic expansion starting in 1999, providing that
"international crises" do not have a dampening effect.
</P>
<P>
The institute said that if economic turmoil were to hit the
European Union, then the repercussions would be extremely serious
"given the strong integration of our industrial system."
</P>
<P>
It said that a crisis within the EU would affect a large number
of sectors and drag down the entire manufacturing system.
</P>
<P>
But Prometeria said that a deterioration in the economy of
eastern European countries would have "marginal effects" on
Italy's industrial production.
</P>
<P>
If the US economy were to fall into recession, Prometeria said
the effects would be limited to a small number of sectors which
have recently expanded into the US market.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the turbulence on the international scene, Prometeria
foresees an increase in domestic demand, especially for investment
products and durable goods, which will allow industrial production
to maintain a healthy growth rate," the research center
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
