<HEADLINE> 925 Sri Lankan Soldiers Killed, Missing In Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A total of 22 army officers and
903 soldiers had been killed or missing in action during Tamil
rebel attacks last week in the Northern Province, according to the
Island newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
A further 25 officers and 401 soldiers had been wounded in the
action and at least 717 Tamil terrorists were killed and 1,100
others wounded, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC) had
transferred the bodies of 684 army personnel from the Tamil rebels
to the government, the report quoted the military sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The town of Kilinochchi, which was held by the troops since it
was captured in November 1996, was assaulted last week by the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels who wanted to
capture this prime location on the main supply route from South to
North.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were successful in forcing the troops to retreat to
Parandan where the fierce battle continued, the report said.
</P>
<P>
With the rebels concentrating on the re-capture of Kilinochchi
government troops were able to recapture Mankulam, a town over 10
kilometers South which had been earlier held by the LTTE rebels
and the troops failed to recapture it despite five months of
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The troops, who have been engaged in clearing a 75-kilometer
supply route to the North under a major offensive codenamed
"Operation Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory) since May last year,
have recaptured only 45 kilometers so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
