<HEADLINE> No Ground for Military Action Against Yugoslavia: Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy reiterated Thursday that
there are no premises for military action against Yugoslavia and any
such action must be legitimized within the framework of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Romano Prodi made the statement in a telephone
conversation with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov,
according to the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said, "The Italian government believes there are no
premises for military action against the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia." Any military action of this nature "must be
legitimized within the U.N. framework", he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Italy fully supports U.N. Security Council resolution
1199 and is asking for its full application, especially for the
withdrawal of Serb police and military units and an end to the
repression of ethnic Albanians."
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, Primakov briefed Prodi on the meeting
between Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on Thursday morning, and Belgade's
willingness to accept a mission sent to the southern province of
Kosovo by the Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe
with no reservations attached.
</P>
<P>
Primakov expressed his hope that on the Kosovo issue, Russia
could get more support and cooperation from Italy.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, a NATO source said the withdrawal of Serb forces
has been "totally inadequate because there are still 11,500 men in
special units in the province" and thousands of army troops.
</P>
<P>
"In the 15 days since the U.N. resolution was passed, Milosevic
has not respected the request of the international community,"
added the source.
</P>
<P>
The source also said it seemed that the civilian population is
still being intimidated and that Milosevic's units "appear to be
preparing to stay in the area during the winter".
</P>
<P>
From early this year, ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, accounting
for 90 percent of Kosovo's population, have been fighting for
independence. The issue has drawn international attention, and
NATO has been threatening to launch air strikes against
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
