<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay's Parliament Approves Anti-Drug Dealing Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The parliament of Uruguay has
approved a law to prevent drug-trafficking and money-laundering,
local newspapers reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The law forbids the planting, harvesting and commercial
exploitation of any crop from which narcotics can be obtained.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, any individual who deals with drugs will
be punished with a jail term ranging from 20 months to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Organizing or financing criminal activities will be punished
with prison terms ranging from 20 months to 8 years. These terms
will apply also to anyone who introduces drugs into Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The sentence will be harsher if victims of these crimes are
under 18 years of age, disabled, if the drug is provided without
consent, or if the sale of narcotics takes place inside or around
schools.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the law empowers the judiciary to bypass bank
privacy and to investigate cases of money-laundering as part of
international cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
