<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ranks 8th in Overseas Tourism Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China now ranks 8th in the
world in earnings from overseas tourism, according to information
provided for "World Travel Day" ceremonies in the city of
Chongqing, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
China received more than 50 million tourists in 1997, and earned 12
billion U.S. dollars from related services.
</P>
<P>
The country rank 41st in 1978 when it began to open to the
outside world and earnings from overseas tourism only stood at
around 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the tourism industry also earned more than 20
billion yuan from over 600 million domestic tourists.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, there were increases in
arrivals from all overseas tourist markets except Asia. The number
of tourists from other Asian countries fell eight percent in the
eight months.
</P>
<P>
Some 41 million overseas tourists visited China from January to
August, up 12 percent from the same period last year, and related
earnings amounted to 8.2 billion U.S. dollars, up 5.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Labor Talks Stall, Sides to Meet Again Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The resumption of
negotiations today between the NBA and its players union did
nothing to raise hopes that the regular season will begin as
scheduled on November 3.
</P>
<P>
Although the five-hour meeting -- the first between the sides
since August 6 -- was described as "cordial," by NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik, the prevailing air of pessimism heading
into the proceedings was realized as both sides refused to give
ground. Another meeting is set for Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly did not make any progress in terms of reaching
any agreements," Granik said. "Perhaps we made progress in terms
of the players understanding our position."
</P>
<P>
A formal decision about the cancellation of regular-season
games is expected to be made next week, but it looks likely that
the league will lose regular-season to a labor stoppage for the
first time in its 52-year history.
</P>
<P>
The owner-imposed lockout, in effect since midnight June 30,
has already led to the cancellation of the entire preseason
schedule.
</P>
<P>
Today, Players Association representatives went over a
proposal they soundly criticized from the league less than two
weeks ago. It is expected they will present a counterproposal
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The major stumbling block is the league's attempt to put a
ceiling on salaries and install a hard cap by phasing out the
Larry Bird exception. The union says the Bird exception, the
clause in the previous agreement that allows teams to re-sign
free agents without regard to the salary cap, is not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
Along with phasing out the Bird exception, the latest owner's
proposal also deals with the elimination of the three-year rookie
scale, which allows third-year players unrestricted free agency
after their third season with the team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several NBA players have attended practice sites
and workout facilities this week to discuss the lockout with fans
and media.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are awaiting the ruling of arbitrator John Feerick
on a grievance filed by the Players Association hours before the
owners imposed the lockout.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of which way John Feerick rules, this is only
going to get settled with the players at the bargaining table,"
NBA commissioner David Stern said.
</P>
<P>
The union claims NBA players have guaranteed contracts that s
hould allow them to be paid during the lockout. Thg NBA contends
its actions are entirely legal during a work stoppage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olano Wins Time Trial Gold in Cycling Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Abraham Olano shook off a knee
injury to win his second world title in three years at the world
cycling championships in Valkenburg, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish rider had to fight the pain of a knee injury
during the 43.5km elite time trial over a hilly course but still
triumphed by 37 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Olano averaged 47.8kph in cold, wet conditions to beat
compatriot Melchior Mauri. Ukrainian Sergei Gontchar took the
bronze medal, 47 seconds behind Olano.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 Olano won the world road race title ahead of the
all-conquering Miguel Indurain who beat him for the gold medal in
the world time trial that year in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
A year later he shared the Olympic podium with his fellow
Spaniard who took the time trial title in Atlanta with Olano
again the silver medalist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
