<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Thursday that he
had authorized U.S. participation in air strikes by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) against Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In remarks during a health care speech at the White House,
Clinton indicated a growing impatience with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to comply with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday I decided that the United States would vote to give
NATO the authority to carry out military strikes against Serbia if
President Milosevic continues to defy the international
community," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"In the days ahead, my counterparts in Europe will be making
similar decisions," he added. (US-Clinton-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin expressed "regret" in
connection with the statement by State Duma Chairman Gennady
Seleznyov calling for a referendum on confidence in the president,
presidential press secretary Dmitry Yakushkin said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov called for a referendum on the removal of the
Russian president at a press conference on Thursday, a day after
the nationwide protest actions, during which the main political
demand was for the president's early resignation.
</P>
<P>
According to Seleznyov, "after this large-scale action of
protest which took place on Wednesday it would be more legitimate
to call a referendum in Russia on whether society trusts or does
not trust the president, on whether the president should or should
not resign." (Russia-Yeltsin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. House of Representatives have begun
debating whether to launch an impeachment inquiry of President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The House leadership has granted a Democratic request to expand
debate on the impeachment inquiry resolution submitted by the
Judiciary Committee to two hours rather than the one hour
originally planned. (US-House-Scandal-Inquiry) 
</P>
