<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Constructs Facilities for the Handicapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China has begun to construct
more facilities for the handicapped in public places.
</P>
<P>
The Fangzhuang residential area of the Fengtai District of
Beijing is one of three pilot areas for the construction of
facilities for the disabled in the Asia-Pacific region. The other
two are in India's capital, New Delhi, and Thailand's capital,
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Government and the China Handicapped
Federation jointly supervised the construction of facilities in
this Beijing neighborhood, and forty council members of the China
Welfare Fund for the Handicapped recently inspected the new
projects there.
</P>
<P>
The new facilities encompass 23 public places, including
kindergartens, shops, hospitals, post offices, banks and streets,
all of which now provide conveniences for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
The central government also promulgated a series of related
laws and regulations to promote progress of the
construction. Fifty-six key projects in Beijing for the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China are
taking the building of facilities for the handicapped into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that construction costs for facilities for the
handicapped will be quite low, compared with the transformation of
existing buildings and roads.
</P>
<P>
Facility construction for the handicapped has become part of
building plans all over the world in the past few years to
provide convenient access and safety for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
