<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Sticks to Free-Float System: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
not change the free foreign exchange system despite a need to have
a system enabling the government to supervise the flows of foreign
exchange, particularly that of export earnings, a minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to change the system," Coordinating Minister
for Economy, Finance and Industry Ginanjar Kartasasmita said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the statement in response to a question on
whether the government would maintain the free floating foreign
exchange system amid a phenomenon that the rupiah has continued to
strengthen against the U.S. dollar in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah flexed its muscles on Thursday, soaring to 8,900
against the U.S. dollar on the back of Japanese yen's impressive
performance.
</P>
<P>
The strengthening rupiah lifted the Jakarta Stocks. The Jakarta
Composite Index rocketed 8.4 percent to close at 288.55 on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with President B.J. Habibie here late Thursday,
Ginanjar said the government perhaps needed a system which could
help it report and supervise the flows of foreign exchange,
especially that of export earnings.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, he said, the International Monetary Fund
had been asked to give inputs on this matter but the government
would not take a hasty decision.
</P>
<P>
If the supervising system was implemented, businessmen would
remain free to bring their foreign exchange in or out of the
country, Ginanjar was quoted by Antara News Agency Friday as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
