<HEADLINE> Dow Makes Dramatic Comeback Despite Other Stocks Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average of 30 major companies Thursday ended with a dramatic
comeback from a 274-point drop, averting a potentially ruinous
slide below this summer's lows.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed just 9.78 points lower at 7,731.91 despite
sliding within 68 points of 7,400, a level that served as the
turning point in the summer selloff that climaxed on September 1.
</P>
<P>
The selling frenzy in the morning was caused by sliding of U.S.
dollars in currency markets and fueled by discouraging comments
from some prominent analysts, including Goldman Sacks strategist
and long-time bull Abby Joseph Cohen.
</P>
<P>
However, most stocks were not so lucky as Dow Jones Thursday at
Wall Street as the market is still plagued by unanswered questions
about big company profits, hedge funds, global economics and the
threat of a U.S. recession.
</P>
<P>
The number of stocks that fell outnumbered those that rose by
more than a 6-to-1 margin at the closing bell.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell as much as 105
points, trading below 1,400 for the first time in 16 months,
before finishing 43.49 points lower at 1,419.12, a loss of 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 finished 11.24 points lower at 959.44
after recovering from a 47-point drop earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was down 7.48 at 477.20, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 22.02 at 563.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany May Not Participate in Possible Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Germany would apparently not be
able to participate in a possible NATO military intervention in
Kosovo soon because of a political standstill after the September
27 general election, German press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder Thursday held brief
discussions with the outgoing chancellor Helmut Kohl on the Kosovo
issue just hours before he left for Washington for a one-day
visit. However, both of them did not made any comment after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The message Schroeder takes to Washington is that the new
German government would support a NATO operation in Kosovo but
German forces could not take part anytime soon because of the
transition of government, said the Berliner Morgenpost newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's government previously already offered 14 Tornado jets
for possible NATO air strikes in Kosovo. But such a deployment
must be approved by parliament.
</P>
<P>
A parliament vote is difficult to arrange at the moment because
the old parliament is already out of session while the new one is
not due to convene before October 26. It would take several days
to call the old parliament into a special session for any vote on
the Kosovo issue, German news agency DPA said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover German political parties still differ on whether there
is sufficient legal basis for a NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
The Greens party, which is the most likely junior partners in
the new German government, stressed Thursday that it would oppose
any German participation in a NATO military action in Kosovo
without a UN resolution approving the use of force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
