<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA: BSkyB/Man United Deal Not Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The English Football Association
confirmed Thursday that it had written to the Office of Fair
Trading (OFT) claiming BSkyB's 623m bid to buy Manchester United
"is not welcomed."
</P>
<P>
News of the FA's bid to block the deal comes as the OFT admits
receiving 350 complaints opposing the deal.
</P>
<P>
An F.A. spokeswoman confirmed comments attributed to F.A.
Chairman Keith Wiseman in which he expressed concern that the
deal could make United too powerful.
</P>
<P>
"The F.A. have written to the OFT saying that if the bid is
allowed to go through it will create a situation where not only
the strength of one club but also the influence of one club would
extend far beyond the range of others. The overall message we
have conveyed is this is not something to be welcomed," FA
chairman Keith Wiseman tells the Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
"Our opinion has been reached on our football feelings. You
can't put a finger on the mischief but most people have a gut
feeling that the bid is not right. It will produce some
distortions, " he added.
</P>
<P>
The OFT will decide on November 2 whether to refer the
takeover to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Three hundred and fifty responses is an unusually high
number-there is no doubt about it," said an OFT spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Usually we get complaints about takeovers from the companies'
rivals but here we have had a large number of complaints from the
fan base."
</P>
<P>
The OFT has until November 2 to consider the 623 million pound
(1.07 billion U.S. dollars) bid for United by BSkyB, a company
controlled by media mogul Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
</P>
<P>
The OFT will then advise the government Department of Trade
and Industry whether it believes the bid should be cleared or
face further scrutiny by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
</P>
<P>
BSkyB holds the rights to live action in the premier league
until 2001.
</P>
<P>
The United board has recommended acceptance of the bid. Sir
Roland Smith, chairman of the United Plc board, told shareholders
this week that BSkyB would not interfere in team affairs or
player acquisitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981009.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hearts Lose UEFA Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA dismissed on Thursday Scottish premier league side Hearts'
appeal to have their European Cup Winners' Cup defeat against
Mallorca overturned.
</P>
<P>
Hearts had made a formal complaint to UEFA over the height of
the goal posts following the match against the Spanish club last
week.
</P>
<P>
The Edinburgh club, who drew 1-1 to go out 2-1 on aggregate,
said the UEFA delegate at the match found that one of the
goalposts at each end was too high due to an uneven pitch.
</P>
<P>
Hearts' chief executive Chris Robinson said the goalposts were
10 centimeters higher than their regulation height of 2.44 meters.
</P>
<P>
But UEFA rejected their appeal on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hearts spokesman Douglas Dalgleish said: "We've lost the
appeal...UEFA say the result must stand.
</P>
<P>
"They haven't given us a reason yet. That will come on Friday
morning, in writing, and then we will be able to decide how to
proceed," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
