<HEADLINE> Thailand, Holland Asked to Set up Interest Sections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Holland will
be asked to set up interest sections in their embassies in Jakarta
and Lisbon for Indonesia and Portugal respectively, according to
an agreement between Indonesia and Portugal here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after two days of talks in New York
between senior officials of the two countries on the question of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The talks, a follow-up to the talks between Annan and the
Foreign Ministers of Indonesia and Portugal in early August, were
chaired by Jamsheed Marker, Personal Representative of U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Marker told reporters that "in a constructive and friendly
atmosphere", they focused also on a U.N. proposal "providing
substantive elements for achieving a just, comprehensive and
internationally acceptable solution" to the question of East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
Further discussions on the subject will be held on November
10-21.
</P>
<P>
The third item on their agenda was the All-inclusive Intra-East
Timor Dialogue (AIETD) to take place in Austria from October 31 to
November 3.
</P>
<P>
Marker said he was very satisfied with the progress of the
Indonesia-Portugal dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"We have a great deal to do as yet and a long way to go, but
the willingness to find a compromise and the atmosphere in the
negotiations is very positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Portugal severed diplomatic relations with Indonesia in 1975
following the Indonesian occupation of East Timor, a former
Portugal colony.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, which has never recognized Indonesian
sovereignty over East Timor, has been calling for a just,
comprehensive and internationally acceptable solution to the
question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
