<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says U.S. Ready for Air Strikes in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Thursday that he had authorized U.S. participation in air
strikes by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) against
Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In remarks during a health care speech at the White House,
Clinton indicated a growing impatience with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to comply with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday I decided that the United States would vote to give
NATO the authority to carry out military strikes against Serbia if
President Milosevic continues to defy the international
community," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"In the days ahead, my counterparts in Europe will be making
similar decisions," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton's move
did not indicate that any military action was imminent.
</P>
<P>
An "activation order" for NATO military action is expected as
early as this weekend unless Milosevic complies with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the United States was confident that ultimately
NATO would reach a consensus in favor of the strikes. Italy has
said the West needs a U.N. legal mandate for intervention.
</P>
<P>
Clinton argued that because of Milosevic's "unconscionable"
action, there was now a danger of violence spreading to
neighboring countries and a humanitarian crisis developing as
winter sets in on the refugees.
</P>
<P>
"We would far prefer to secure President Milosevic's compliance
with the will of the international community in a peaceful
manner," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"But NATO must be prepared to act militarily to protect our
interests and to prevent another humanitarian catastrophe in the
Balkans," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said U.S. ambassador Richard Holbrooke in meetings this
week had made "absolutely clear" what Milosevic must do to avoid
military action.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is simple," Clinton said. "It is full compliance with
the United Nations Security Council resolutions by President
Milosevic," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On September 23, the U.N. Security Council approved a
resolution calling Yugoslavia to stop fighting in Kosovo, pull
back forces, allow relief agencies to get access to the refugees
and start negotiations with ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
