<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Not to Intervene Militarily in Kosovo: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Romania cannot be commanded to
intervene militarily in Kosovo, chief of the Romanian Army's
General Staff Constantin Degeratu said Thursday at the Victoria
Palace government's head office.
</P>
<P>
He said that a decision regarding a certain military solution
linked to this conflict has already been taken at NATO level. "I
know no other country has been called or has offered itself to
participate in the conflict in Yugoslavia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Degeratu said that Romania has "normal" relations with
Yugoslavia and that "our country's actions are based on a good
neighborliness" within these relations.
</P>
<P>
"Romania, as a member of the U.N. and the Partnership for Peace
plan, is compelled to comply with the U.N. decisions and try to
find better solutions to diminish the negative consequences of the
Kosovo conflict," Degeratu said.
</P>
<P>
The latest development of the Kosovo crisis and especially
NATO's possible military intervention in the region are sources of
worry for the whole nation of Romania, a friendly and immediate
neighbor of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu Thursday afternoon
consulted with the ruling coalition party leaders on the evolution
of Kosovo after his Wednesday meeting on the issue with the prime
minister, the defense minister, the foreign minister and the chief
of the General Staff.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Council of National Defense is expected to meet
Sunday at the request of the Romanian president to discuss the
situation in Kosovo, sources in the presidency announced.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government Thursday also discussed the Kosovo
issue at its weekly meeting. "Romania will not deny its
commitments that derive from the Partnership for Peace plan in
which Romania is a member and, according to the U.N. resolutions,
it will not have the obligation to participate in military
actions," Rasvan Popescu, the government spokesman said after the
meeting. He added, "Political and humanitarian support is
inevitable."
</P>
<P>
As stressed by the authorities, Romania has supported all the
diplomatic efforts enacted by the contact group, the NATO member
states and the Security Council in order to find a negotiated
solution to Kosovo that should avoid the use of force, hinder
humanitarian disasters, allow the observance of the fundamental
rights of all the citizens in Kosovo, maintain the territorial
integrity of the Yugoslav Federation and remove the spectrum of
conflict in the Balkans as much as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
