<HEADLINE> Contact Group Ministers Meet on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The six-nation Contact Group on
former Yugoslavia Thursday expressed their endorsement to U.S.
Special envoy Richard Holbrooke's new efforts to end the worsening
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after an emergency meeting of the Contact
Group foreign ministers, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said
that Holbrook would hold another round of talks with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic Friday to put forward six demands for
a full end to various violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The demands are: an end to violence, the withdrawal of security
forces and heavy weapons, free access for humanitarian agencies,
full cooperation with an international war crimes tribunal, the
return of refugees and a start to negotiations on self-rule with
Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, including the United States, Russia,
Britain, France, Germany and Italy did not explicitly refer to the
threat of military action if Milosevic did not comply with the U.N.
Security Council resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We would not invite Russia to approve the use of force. That
is a matter for NATO," Cook said, adding that NATO would meet
within a few days to consider the use of force if Milosevic
refused to back down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
