<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Scientists Discover Gene for Cell Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from the Max
Planck Institute of Biophysical Chemistry in Gottingen, Germany,
have found a gene named Apaf1 which is a key component of cell
death, also known as apoptosis, according to a press release
issued Wednesday by the Institute.
</P>
<P>
They said that this gene can act as a switch in the chain of
the molecular and could lead to the death of a cell.
</P>
<P>
The scientists used mice in their studies to decipher the role
of this gene and they found that this gene is important for the
embryoal development of the mouse. They were also able to better
define the position of the corresponding gene products in the
hierarchy of events which lead to cell death.
</P>
<P>
Life without death is inconceivable. Cell death is vital for an
organism. If apoptosis does not take place, the effects can be
serious. Certain forms of cancer and autoimmune disease can be
tracked back to a lack of apoptosis; the death of nerve cells in
certain forms of Alzheimer's disease and also possibly the damage
done to brain after a stroke are the result of too much apoptosis.
</P>
<P>
They said that Apaf1 gene could become a very attractive object
for many areas of medical research, for the development of new
anti-cancer strategies, the treatment of neurodegenerative disease
such as Alzheimer's and other genetic diseases, which involve a
malfunction of the apoptosis pathway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
