<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt. Rejects Striking Teachers' Offer to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government cannot
reopen negotiations with teachers under duress unless their union
Kalonzo Musyoka told Parliament Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a lengthy ministerial statement, Musyoka said that he was
not ready to negotiate with people who have "thrown a rope around
my neck".
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government signed the pay rise agreement last
December just before the second multi-party general elections.
The increases are by as much as 200 percent spread over five
years.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of teachers started strike in confrontation
with the police across Kenya Monday in a desperate bid to press
the government to implement its pledges of teachers' pay rise.
</P>
<P>
However, Musyoka told parliament his ministry has
allocated 44 billion Shillings (about 733 million U.S. Dollars)
in the budget, out of which 37 billion Shillings goes to
teachers' pay, leaving only 7.2 billion Shillings for development
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Almost 20,000 Kenyan teachers, who are not union members and
have not been reporting to work since the strike, were sacked
by the Teachers Service Commission Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The strike, called by the 250,000-strong Kenya National Union
of Teachers (KNUT), is the third this year. At least 21
opposition members of parliament have openly supported the
strike.
</P>
<P>
Teachers' salaries range from 2,700 Shillings to 29,000
Shillings (45 to 480 U.S. Dollars) a month, relatively higher
than most other civil servants in the east African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
