<HEADLINE> Sudanese Refugees Flee Congo (K) for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- About 8,000 Sudanese refugees
have been forced to return home, fleeing insecurity in the
Democratic Republic of Congo, the World Vision aid agency said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees arrived in Western Equatoria of Sudan Wednesday
after their camps have been burned out in the east of the Congo.
The invaders are unidentified.
</P>
<P>
A large number of refugees, especially mothers and childrens,
remain stranded near the Sudanese border, urgently needing
transportation, according to the World Vision report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted local authorities in Yambio, Sudan, as
saying that 36,000 more refugees could also cross the
Congolese-Sudanese border in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
It said international aid agencies working in the Western
Equatoria area will convene in Nairobi Monday to "further develop
a relief response."
</P>
<P>
"We will strive to provide adequate food and non-food
commodities for their short-term well-being, as well as
transportation to suitable settlement," said World Vision Sudan
food security coordinator Philip Tanner.
</P>
<P>
"Once the situation is controlled, we will begin a dialog on
the longer term needs for a stable reintegration of those
returning to their homes," he added.
</P>
<P>
The returnee originally fled southern Sudan following fighting
between the Sudan Peoples Liberation Army and the Khartoum
government in 1991. They subsequently settled in eastern Congo.
</P>
</TEXT>
